VThe shale gas revolution has made natural gas so cheap that it is displacing coal as a fuel.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPresident Obama\u2019s recently proposed regulations to limit carbon-dioxide emissions from new power plants have been much heralded by environmentalists because they would make new coal-fired power plants too costly to operate. In truth, they accomplish almost nothing. These rules would apply to new power plants only. But few new coal-fired power plants or units have been built in recent years because of the low price of natural gas, and few are planned over the next five years, according to the federal Energy Information Agency. Most modern gas-fired electric plants meet the standard the president is proposing, so the rules are irrelevant for them.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTo meet these new rules, proposed last month, new coal-fired power plants would have to capture carbon dioxide from smokestacks before it is emitted and then send it by pipeline to a location where it would be pumped underground for long-term isolation. The Environmental Protection Agency says this technology, known as carbon capture and storage, can be made ready for large-scale use. But most experts - including me - would say \u201cnot yet,\u201d because it has not been tested at the required scale.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe shale gas revolution has made natural gas so cheap that it is displacing coal as a fuel for generating electricity. For utilities that burn natural gas, this has meant higher profits and lower costs for customers. Electricity production from coal has dropped from nearly 50 per cent of the total five years ago to under 40 per cent in 2012, while electricity from gas has risen from about 20 per cent five years ago to 30 per cent in 2012, according to the energy department.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPrice has tilted the playing field to make gas the preferred source of fuel for generating electricity, and because natural gas produces half as much carbon dioxide as coal when burned, this transition has already reduced emissions of the greenhouse gas in the United States. To speed the transition to gas, we could tilt the playing field more by imposing a tax on carbon emissions, but given the politics in Washington today, that is for another time.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAs for capturing and storing carbon dioxide, the EPA cites as an example the oil industry\u2019s successful use of carbon dioxide captured from industrial smokestacks to stimulate the flow of oil out of old wells. But the EPA\u2019s point is irrelevant because the amount of capacity for storage of carbon dioxide in the old wells is tiny compared with what is produced in the generation of electricity, so the challenge is fundamentally different. There is potential large-capacity underground storage in deep saline aquifers, but no one knows if these can contain carbon dioxide for centuries without leaking. If I were on a technical panel recommending what to do, I would say that carbon capture and storage is not ready for large-scale use.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLimit mercury emissions\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhat the EPA should do first is aggressively enforce limits on mercury emissions from power plants that were imposed in 2012. Those standards will be phased in over the next three to four years and should force the dirtiest of the old coal-fired power plants to shut down by requiring expensive new technology. Those plants had been exempted from limits on emissions of sulfur-dioxide and nitrogen-oxide and have no scrubbers to capture those pollutants before they go up the smokestack. Newer plants, by contrast, have scrubbers that can be tweaked to take care of mercury.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aNext, the administration should get serious about regulating carbon dioxide from existing power plants. President Obama has promised to develop standards for those plants in the coming months, though he says they will be less stringent than those for new plants.In 