VWARSAW: The devastation caused by Typhoom Haiyan in Philippines, which left as many as 3200 dead continues to cast a shadow on climate talks in Warsaw . Together with Philippines climate change commissioner and negotiator Yeb Sano\u2019s continuing fast at the UN climate change meet may have forced countries to move towards addressing the devastating impacts experienced by countries that have contributed the least to the problem.While the images from Philippines dominate the imagination at Warsaw, the adverse impacts of climate change are now becoming all to familiar. This year saw the devastation in Uttarakhand and Cyclone Phailin in India to droughts in Africa , and experts say that each of these disasters have been exacerbated by unchecked climate change caused by failure to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and inability of countries to adapt to changes caused by climate change.This has led to a situation, known in UN climate change negotiations parlance, of permanent \u201closs and damage\u201d. Proposed as a new pillar, beyond emission reduction and adapting to climate change, loss and damage implicitly places the blame of climate change at the doorstep of the industrialised countries.At Warsaw, government representatives have been working over the weekend to put in place a proposal that address ways to address the devastating impacts of climate change. The proposal will be taken up by ministers for discussions over the next week.Marcin Korolec, Poland's environment minister and president of the UN sponsored talks in Warsaw said earlier this week that the \u201closs and damage issue is part of the imminent political discussion. We are confident that we will have a decision \u2026 by the end of the conference next week. Although the positions of different countries today are quite different, there is room for consensus.\u201dThe proposal pushed by the developing countries bloc G-77 and China calls for an institutional mechanism to address global response to loss and damage. There has been strong opposition from the United States, which is concerned about possible litigation that would arise from accepting \u201closs and damage\u201d as something separate from adapting to climate change. Norwayhas also not been in favour of a new mechanism, while the European Union has been openly ambivalent.Talks late night on Saturday, saw the United States indicating that it was open to the idea of a transitional committee to begin the work towards setting up an institutional mechanism. A negotiator involved in the loss and damage talks said \u201cthe United States continues to oppose the idea of compensation for loss and damage, there are many other technical aspects of loss and damage that need to be address urgently and these even the US can\u2019t ignore.\u201dSources indicated that there is a move among industrialised countries to consider setting up an international mechanism to deal with the impact of extreme events like cyclones and typhoons and slow onset events like changing rainfall pattern in developing countries. The mechanism will have a technical facility to manage information and data as well as assist in the development of new tools and approaches and help build capacity to address the loss and damage resulting from adverse effects of climate change.\u201cThe ministers will take a call on the institutional mechanism for loss and damage. We want to see a repeat of the unity among the developing countries as we saw in Doha,\u201d said Harjeet Singh, international co-ordinator, Action AidWith scientists now more sure than ever before that human activity is responsible for climate change, it is now clear that countries that have contributed to the least to climate change are most vulnerable to its impacts. There has been a growing demand from the developing countries to address these devastating impacts of climate change, which cant be tackled by reducing emissions and adapting to the changes.\u201cStrong institutional mechanism on loss and damage will eventually drive stronger action on emission reduction and adapting to climate change,\u201d said Singh.
