VUntiring in his quest to change the way the world consumes energy, 58-year old Vinod Khosla has in the last decade backed startups developing energy efficiency products, healthcare solutions and alternative foods. His eponymously-named fund, Khosla Ventures, which raised $1.3 billion (Rs 8,100 crore) in 2011, boasts an eclectic portfolio ranging from precision agriculture to internal combustion engines. Doggedness and an ability to embrace failure have made this IIT-Delhi graduate one of the most celebrated investors in Silicon Valley. The winner of The Economic Times Global Indian of the Year 2013 award, Khosla shared his thoughts on his investment philosophy with ET in an email interview. Edited Excerpts\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHow do you see the future of energy?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is possible the existing technology will be able to handle the growth in demand for energy and resources, but they will do so only at an increasing cost. This places a growing drag on the economy in the long-term and will create an increased systemic risk. Instead, we can invent and commercialise new technologies that provide far better alternatives to the current methods. We have to focus on inventing resource \u201cmultipliers\u201d instead of just trying to \u201cdiscover\u201d more oil. We need inventions across a broad range of sustainable technologies, including utility-scale clean energy generation like solar thermal, distributed generation like rooftop solar or efficient power generation engines for buildings, more efficient engines, batteries, biofuels, biochemicals, new materials like glass that block light at the push of abutton, as well as food and agriculture systems.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhich of these will prove to be most impactful in the next few years?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSpecifics here are impossible to predict with any real accuracy. However, we can point to a few key fundamental energy needs that we have to solve. Distributed storage and generation just makes sense, and I suspect we will see a lot of breakthroughs here. We\u2019ve got to get off our reliance on conventional oil, and I\u2019m a big supporter of alternative fuels. New battery technology is the single key enabler for electric cars, and we will likely see more coming out of this area as well. I wish nuclear, especially fusion, were on the list but that seems somewhat unlikely.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhat role do you see for innovation in the food sector?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWe have to solve the animal husbandry problem. Meat production requires the most amount of land and a disproportionately large amount of other resources. One kilogram of red meat takes 7.25 kg of grain and more than 6,800 litre of water, and 4.4 megajoule of energy to produce. This is a very resourceintense process and animal farming contributes 18% of all greenhouse gas effects. This can be made more efficient and innovation is the only path for solving this. We will see a lot of change throughout the food supply chain. There\u2019s already been a lot of work done at the seed level, but we will see more when it comes to farming, the creation of products that are nearly perfect replacements for meat from taste down to the cooking process itself as well as information technology areas, referred to as precision agriculture.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhich sectors will receive most dollars from Khosla Ventures in future and why?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s impossible to plan ahead when it comes to innovation. We have invested into a number of promising new areas including healthcare, new computing platforms, robotics and food but there is still a lot to do in internet and mobile as well. We continue to invest in sustainability, but it\u2019s even harder to predict there because so much depends on large scientific breakthroughs.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
