VSHIMLA: In the past during winters, rivers in Himachal Pradesh used to witness very less discharge of water due to extreme cold freezing the glaciers from where rivers originate. But now, water discharge during winters has increased due to melting of glaciers and early melting of seasonal snow. While study has revealed that since 1962, the glacier area has reduced from 2,077 square km to 1,628 square km, another study has found that many small glaciers have already disappeared from the Himalayas.A paper "Effect of Global Warming on the Himalayan Cryosphere" by A V Kulkarni from Space Application Centre (ISRO), Ahmedabad, revealed that investigation of 466 glaciers in Chenab, Parbati and Baspa basins of Himachal Pradesh has shown overall de-glaciation of 21%. However, number of glaciers has increased due to fragmentation, it said.The paper states that average stream runoff of Baspa basin (in Kinnaur district) for December has increased by 75%. "This combination of glacial retreat, negative mass balance, early melting of seasonal snow cover and winter time increase in stream runoff suggest an influence of climate change on the Himalayan Cryosphere," it added.Another paper "Global Climate Change and Melting of Himalayan Glaciers" by Samjwal Ratna Bajracharya, Pradeep Kumar Mool, Basanta Raj Shrestha from International Centre for Integrated Mountain Development (ICIMOD), Kathmandu, said that global mean temperature is expected to increase between 1.4 to 5.8C over the next 100 years. Consequences of this change in global climate are already being witnessed in the Himalayan glaciers and glacial lakes. The Himalayan glaciers are retreating at rates ranging from 10 to 60 metres per year and many small glaciers have already disappeared.A report prepared by State Centre on Climate Change , Himachal Pradesh, said that based on the recent observations on Himalayan glaciers, it is observed that most of them are retreating. "Monitoring of these glaciers would be helpful to assess future availability of Himalayan water resources," it stated.State Centre on Climate Change for the study had monitored the glaciers of Baspa and Spiti sub-catchment of Satluj river basin. On the basis of updated inventory of the glaciers in Baspa basin, a total of 30 glaciers could be mapped. Of these, 19 glaciers were selected to estimate glacier retreat."Investigation reveals that almost all glaciers are receding and an overall 19% deglaciation is observed from 1962 to 2001. Glacier located around 5,000m have shown 24% loss as compared to 14% for those located on the altitude higher than 5,400m, and the mean altitude of the glacier terminus is shifted upward by 88m that is from 4,482 to 4,570," said the report.
