VAround 300 million people, or a quarter of the population of India, the third largest economy in Asia, do not have access to electricity.\u000a\u000aFatih Birol, chief economist at Paris-based International Energy Agency (IEA), in an interview spoke about India\u2019s ambitious green energy targets. He said it is achievable with the right regulatory push and incentives for developers.\u000a\u000aBirol also took India\u2019s side in the trade battle between India and the US at the World Trade Organization (WTO), where a dispute settlement panel is hearing the US\u2019s complaints against India\u2019s domestic content requirements for procurement of solar cells and modules under the Jawaharlal Nehru National Solar Mission (JNNSM).\u000a\u000aHe also said India should leverage the current crude oil price scenario to negotiate better terms and review the Asian premium charged by the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (Opec).\u000a\u000aEdited excerpts:\u000a\u000aWhile India wants to promote renewable energy sources, it has been taken to the WTO by the US on the issue of India\u2019s domestic content requirements under the country\u2019s solar power programme. India\u2019s large solar targets will also provide an impetus to manufacturing. Your views on the same?\u000a\u000aIt is an issue between the US and the Indian authorities to deal with, but India has all the right to produce its own domestic energy resources, as all the other countries are attempting to do. Especially for India, when the economy is growing, when more than 300 million people have no access to electricity, Indian efforts in that respect are all legitimate.\u000a\u000aWhile renewables will form a part of India\u2019s energy mix, one can\u2019t wish away the conventional sources. In a depressed oil price scenario, how can a country like India\u2014one of the largest energy importers in the world\u2014leverage this opportunity?\u000a\u000aI think India\u2019s growing reliance on oil imports is not only a challenge for the energy sector, but also to the Indian economy in general, both from a market economy point of view and also from an energy security point of view.\u000a\u000aThere are two measures that can be taken to address this challenge. The first one is there is a very strong growth in car ownership in India. This will grow, which is very much in line with other countries. But we have to make sure that the cars and trucks coming on the streets need to have better energy efficiency and fuel efficiency standards... The second one is to replace imported oil and gas with domestic energy sources, such as renewable energy.\u000a\u000aThis renewable energy will also be helpful in making more diversification in the energy mix.\u000a\u000aOf course, it is not expected that renewables will be the magic bullet to solve all of these problems, but they can make a very handsome contribution.\u000a\u000aIndia imports as much as 77% of its energy needs. How can India leverage depressed oil prices to get better terms?\u000a\u000aIndia shall do two things. One, domestically, the other one, internationally. Domestically, the lower oil prices provide a very good opportunity to reduce subsidies given to oil products, which in turn means putting downward pressure on domestic consumption. This will be helpful.\u000a\u000aSecond, India is a major oil importer and the growing oil importing prospects in the current price environment is a competitive advantage when India discusses the future oil contracts with major oil exporters.\u000a\u000aIndia and other Asian countries, such as Japan, pay an Asian premium to Opec. Do you think such a demand from Opec is justified?\u000a\u000aI think when we look at the oil markets, compared to many many years ago when the Asian premium was introduced; when we compare that time with today, many things have changed in the ways of the market in terms of the source of production, the trade patterns and consumption standards.\u000a\u000aThis is a very good time to review this practice and to provide more fair conditions for all parties.
