VThe scorching of plants reported from various parts of Kerala coast is caused by the salt spray, scientists at Kerala University of Fisheries and Ocean Studies (KUFOS) revealed.\u000a\u000aAfter a scientific observation of the samples of sea water, soil, plants etc. collected from the affected areas, the expert committee comprising of oceanographers, geologists, meteorologists, biologists and chemists have prepared an interim report which ruled out any chances of heat burst.\u000a\u000aThe environment has low temperature during the monsoon season. Heat bursts are local with a maximum of three km stretch and is very rare. \u201cSince this phenomenon happened all along the coast of the State, we rule out the possibilities of heat burst\u201d, said S Suresh Kumar, Professor and the head of the committee.\u000a\u000aThe interim report pointed out that salt nucleus formed from the salt spray due to strong wind caused the wilting of plants. There is high chance of salt spray. Aerosols with high salt content will be formed by the action of wind on wave surfing. Intermittent rain and sun during this monsoon may have aggravated the situation, the report said.\u000a\u000aScientists also observed that the phenomenon was a gradual process and the public came to know of this only at a later stage. Local enquiry confirmed the occurrence of similar phenomena for the last several years during August \u2013September period, but this year it happened earlier in June.\u000a\u000aThis is more likely to be an oceanic process and it should be studied in detail with reference to atmospheric, oceanographic and chemical aspects, B Madhusoodana Kurup, Vice Chancellor, KUFOS said.\u000a\u000aThe expert committee would conduct a detailed survey on oceanographic aspects such as sea surface temperature (SST), sea level rise, variations in tides etc all along the Kerala coast in long term manner in order to study the impact of climate change and associated phenomena, he said.
