VISTANBUL: India\u2019s pledge to cut emission intensity of its GDP by a third in the next 15 years has won handsome praise from the International Energy Agency (IEA), which also sympathises with the country\u2019s view that developing countries should not foot the entire bill to combat climate change as rich nations polluted the planet for a century.\u201cIt shows that India is a respected member of international community and moves alongside with others\u2014 the developed and developing countries\u2014and plays its role to address one of the biggest challenges we are facing today, namely climate change. So this is definitely a move in the right direction. I commend the Indian government for taking this position,\u201d IEA executive director Fatih Barol told ETon the sidelines of the G-20 Energy Ministers Conference in Istanbul.Barol was also sympathetic about India\u2019s view that rich countries need to help developing countries in combating climate change. \u201cI hope that we will have an agreement in Paris this year, and we can only have an agreement in Paris if all the developed and developing countries come together,\u201d he said. \u201cBut we have to be frank. When we look at the emissions in the last 120 years, bulk of the emissions came from the developed countries, and it will be unfair if countries with lower income to get the biggest share of that burden.\u201dHe said regions like Africa had a share of barely 3% of global emissions, but consequences of climate change will be felt most in the continent. \u201cThat\u2019s a very unfair situation. So I hope in Paris we have an agreement, which is global and is also fair based on the past responsibilities and means of the countries taken into consideration,\u201d he said. IEA, the energy watchdog of the developed world, also praised the Narendra Modi government for its ambitious solar energy programme.India wants non-fossil fuels to account for 40% of installed capacity in 15 years with the help of transfer of technology and low-cost international finance, including from Green Climate Fund.\u201cI think the Modi government shows that energy is one of the key priorities for the economic growth of India. This makes me very happy, as an energy man. I believe making most of the domestic sources, including solar, is a very wise move. And at the same time India is pushing the button to use energy more efficiently, and as a result of that India came up with a pledge,\u201d Barol said. India has faced criticism that it hasn\u2019t announced a date when emissions would peak, but the IEA chief was sympathetic.\u201cI wouldn\u2019t compare different countries. Every country has its own domestic situation, economic development levels. I wish to see that all the countries make their best in order to reduce emission. And at the same time by making those efforts they will also reduce local pollution. Indian government is making all the efforts to reduce the environmental footprint of Indian energy sector and at the same time have growth. So growing emphasis of the Modi government on solar power and energy efficiency is very much appreciated,\u201d he said.Ambitious and achievableIndia\u2019s INDC is both ambitious and achievable. New Delhi is building on its 2020 target to reduce the amount of GHG emissions produced for every dollar of economic output. As a result of the efforts outlined in the INDC, India will have a per capita emission of 3.5 tonnes in 2030. While the US and China will both have per capita emissions of 12 tonnes. New Delhi has sought to chart a development path that is cleaner, while at the same time it is mindful of the vast unmet developmental needs of its people.(The author travelled to Istanbul on the invitation of the Turkish G-20 Presidency)
