VMUMBAI: After you've fried those spicy chicken nuggets and drumsticks, what do you do with the leftover oil? Perhaps reuse it for cooking, or dump the grease down the drain. Right?Ever wondered what happens to used cooking oil generated in the kitchens of five-star hotels? Well, in some cases the waste is being put to work, helping power local trains, luxury sedans, Jacuzzi, lifts and hot water boiler operations.Five-star Westin hotel in Singapore deploys used cooking oil from its kitchens to power limousines. Likewise, a five-star hotel brand in India produces its own renewable energy from cooking oil waste for its luxury sedans that ferry guests from the airport to the property.A shunter service between Chennai and Perambur Loco Works in Tamil Nadu is run on biodiesel generated from the used cooking oil provided by The Hilton Chennai. The 253-key hotel churns out about 450 litres of cooking grease waste every month and supplies it to the Indian Railways to be converted into biofuel.At the railways' Parel workshop in Mumbai, forklift trucks operate on biofuel generated from the cooking oil waste produced by Leela Mumbai. "It's a relatively fuss-free process to extract biodiesel from cooking oil. However, there is not much awareness about it and hence we get only a small quantity of used cooking oil," said Narendra Patil, chief PRO, Central Railways.Andre Gomez, head (operations), Hilton Worldwide, said the company "focuses on measuring and managing our waste output and diversions, while also continually looking for creative ways to reduce our waste footprint".Some hotels in India run the entire hot water process at their property using fuel generated from cooking oil waste. The Park Hyatt Hyderabad operates its sauna and steam facilities with energy produced from the hotel's edible cooking oil residue. The 200-plus room property collects cooking oil waste from its restaurants every day and converts it into 300-400 litres of biodiesel to run geysers and Jacuzzi."We do not dump the restaurant grease or used cooking oil. A process is in place to collect the oil from our restaurants and kitchens. It is made to chemically react with an alcohol (like ethanol) to produce fatty acid esters or biodiesel, which is used for the hotel's steam and hot water boiler operation," said Suresh Kumar, director (engineering) at Park Hyatt Hyderabad. Operating a boiler using biodiesel costs the hotel Rs 10 a litre, while diesel costs them Rs 45 a litre. "It helps in having a better control over the hotel's waste," said Kumar.India consumes about 21 million tonnes of edible oils and generates 2 million tonnes of cooking oil waste annually, said Sandeep Chaturvedi, president of Biodiesel Association of India. Hotels are increasingly putting waste cooking oil to good use, reducing carbon emissions, cutting operating costs and improving the energy efficiency. The Radisson Blu Plaza Delhi, Hilton Garden Inn Trivandrum and ITC Maratha Mumbai offer the cooking oil residue to local industries for manufacturing soap, rubber and detergents.At the Grand Hyatt Mumbai, an in-house sewage treatment plant segregates oil from water, which is then treated and used for gardening. The hotel sells the oil residue to local manufacturers. The Park Hyatt Hyderabad is experimenting to produce fuel from plastic waste.Globally, hospitality chains have either set up a micro-refinery or have a tie-up with a biodiesel player to turn waste cooking oil into energy. Though hotels, unlike other sectors like manufacturing, account for only around 1% of emissions, they have taken measures worldwide to reduce their carbon footprint. "As a global company with more than 4,660 hotels in 104 countries, we place high priority on the efficient and responsible use of natural resources and minimizing our impact," said Hilton's Gomez.Hotels normally give their wastes to waste management companies or municipal certified pick-up facilities. Only in some cases, they donate leftovers to charity. Hotels avoid donating leftovers on concerns of people falling ill due to food poisoning, which, they fear, may lead to lawsuits.
