VNEW DELHI: In a big step towards bringing the global climate deal into force before this year end, the United States and China - the world\u2019s top two emitters of greenhouse gases - on Saturday ratified the Paris Agreement which was approved by the 195 countries, including India, in December last year.The move has now put the attention on India and European Union (EU) about the timing of their formally joining the agreement. India is expected to ratify it by the year end.The Paris Agreement will enter into force only after at least 55 countries, accounting for minimum 55 % of total global emissions, deposit their instruments of ratification. So far, 26 countries (accounting for over 39% of the global emission) have ratified the agreementThe Agreement is meant to limit the global warming \u201cwell below\u201d 2C and as close to 1.5C as possible, to increase economic and social ability to adapt to extreme climate and also to direct the scale and speed of global financial flows to match the required low carbon and climate-resilient development. As many as 180 countries, including India, have, so far, signed this agreement. The ratifation is the final step before the global climate deal comes into force.The US President Barack Obama and Chinese President Xi Jinping on Saturday submitted their instruments of ratification to formally join the Paris agreement to the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon ahead of the G20 leaders summit at Hangzhou in China. India\u2019s Prime Minister Narendra Modi will also be there at Hangzhou to attend the G20 summit.Urging world leaders, particularly G20 countries, to accelerate their domestic ratification processes, Ban Ki-moon in Hangzhou said, \u201cWe just need another 29 countries representing 16% of global emissions to bring this Paris Agreement into force. I am hopeful and optimistic that we can do it before the end of this year and before my term as Secretary-General of the United Nations ends\u201d.\u201cI would like today to thank China and the United States for ratifying this landmark agreement\u2014an agreement on which rests the opportunity for a sustainable future for every nation and every person,\u201d said Patricia Espinosa, executive secretary of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).\u201cThe earlier that Paris is ratified and implemented in full, the more secure that future will become," she said in a statement, issued by the UNFCCC from Bonn.The UN Secretary General\u2019s special event in New York on September 21 will offer a further focused opportunity for other countries to join the Paris Agreement.Besides ratifying the Paris Agreement, China and the US on Saturday also announced support for increased action on aviation and refrigerant (HFCs) emissions. Both the countries announced that they were working together to secure a comprehensive and ambitious amendment of a sister treaty - the Montreal Protocol - when governments meet in Kigali, Rwanda in October.The amendment is aimed at managing down the use of climate-damaging Hydroflurocarbons (HFCs) that are now being used in refrigeration systems such as air conditioners. The two countries said they wanted to secure not only an internationally-agreed phase-down of HFCs but an early \u2018freeze\u2019 date so that the phase-down starts sooner rather than later.They also announced backing for action on aviation emissions under the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) at its meeting later this month. Under ICAO, governments will decide whether to agree a market-based mechanism that can assist in encouraging aircraft operators to bring down greenhouse gases from planes.China and the United States said that they plan to be early participants in a voluntary pilot phase if the decision goes through at the ICAO conference.\u201cI would like to commend China and the US for these two additional announcements. While the Paris Agreement is the main vehicle for action on climate change, it is clear that all international agreements need to work in tandem in order to realize our shared goals and aims,\u201d said Patricia Espinosa.The new announcements by China and the US come ahead of the next round of UN climate negotiations - known as COP22 - which is to be held in Marrakech, Morocco in November.
