VMANGALURU: Fate of most natural low lands across the world such as Bangladesh and Male hinges on resolve of parties to adhere to Paris Agreement, an agreement on Climate Change.The Paris Agreement deals with greenhouse gases emissions mitigation, adaptation and finance starting in 2020, noted M R Madhav , professor emeritus, JNT University and visiting professor, IIT, Hyderabad.In his address at the inauguration of 10th International Symposium on Lowland Technology (ISLT) organized by the International Association of Lowland Technology (IALT) and department of civil engineering, NITK , Surathkal, Madhav, said the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) has indicated that the sea level could rise by 0.5 metres in next 50-years. This will threaten existence of Bangladesh, Male and a good part of Krishna- Godavari basin.Madhav, who also heads the IALT, said, the IPCC forecast is based on future scenario for climate change based on global warming and other factors. A lot of this can be mitigated if parties to the Paris Agreement remain true to it, he said. Else, salt water intrusion, and wave action will wreak havoc on the natural lowlands including Sundarbans in West Bengal , which is already shrinking on account of erosion, and this situation could only be hastened, he warned.With pressure on land growing, Madhav, said the future development of humanity will be on reclaimed land. The challenge of an event such as ISLT is to ensure sustainability and development of reclaimed land to foster human development, he said. This is the reason that the Paris Agreement is laying greater emphasis on reducing greenhouse gases emission and switch to green energy such as solar and wind, which countries like Germany, Denmark are already doing.Large scale decimation of natural rain forest in Brazil which accounts for nearly 40-50% of world's natural oxygen supply is also a cause for concern, Madhav said given the rise in greenhouse gases emission. Bhutan is the only nation in the world that is Carbon negative and efforts should be made to address these issues to ensure sustainability of lowland areas. Nobo Mishima, professor, SAKA University, Japan inaugurated ISLT. K N Lokesh, director, NITK, presided.
