VNAGPUR: The state government has decided to implement a Rs4,000 crore World Bank-aided project on climate resilient agriculture. The project will cover around 3,000 drought-prone villages in Marathwada and about 1,000 villages of Vidarbha, mainly the 894 located in saline belt of Amravati division. The project is to be executed in six years.To start with, the agriculture department by a government resolution issued on October 28, has set up a seven-member committee under the chairmanship of principal secretary (agriculture). The committee will now identify 3,000 villages in Marathwada and 1,000 in Vidarbha that will be the focus of the project. The programme aims to reduce farmers\u2019 dependence on unpredictable weather cycles and enhance resilience of agriculture to climate change and vulnerability through research and use of technology.The other members of the committee are Randhir Sawarkar (MLA from Akola west), vice-chancellors of Vasantrao Naik Agriculture University, Parbhani and Panjabrao Deshmukh Agriculture University, Akola, state agriculture commissioner and managing director of groundwater survey and development, Pune. Project director of the state weather-based agriculture project will be the member-secretary.\u201cMarathwada and Vidarbha regions have been at the receiving end of climatic variations. Erratic showers and heavy spells have damaged crops very often in the last few years,\u201d a senior officer of agriculture department said. While in Marathwada the villages will be selected from eight drought-hit districts, the five districts of Amravati division and Wardha in Nagpur district, basically the six farmer suicide-hit districts, could benefit from the project.In Amravati division, large areas in the Purna river valley covering Akola, Amravati and Buldhana districts are affected by saline ingress in agricultural lands, making farming a difficult proposition. Villages will be chosen by the committee on the basis of indicators like weather parameters, agriculture and social backwardness. A cluster approach with adaptability to watershed management will be considered. Various measures will be undertaken to fight drought and minimize impact of weather fluctuations.The project got in-principle approval on July 7. On August 10, a project management unit was set up to prepare an action plan with the approval for a staff of 23 to do the groundwork. At a final meeting under chairmanship of chief minister Devendra Fadnavis , the project was given a go-ahead with the decision to implement it in 4,000 villages of Marathwada and Vidarbha. The idea is to insulate these villages from drought and weather aberrations.
