VNew Delhi: Environmental crisis could become the dominant crisis of the coming years, said leading experts at the Hindustan Times Leadership Summit 2016 on Saturday while batting for planning for next 20-25 years to deal with water crisis which is already a very serious global concern.\u000a\u000a\u201cIndia has got a lot of troubles. You can\u2019t breathe the air, you can\u2019t find water. Indians need to think on this. India dismantled the planning commission, but we need desperate planning to cope up with water crisis and climate change. Water treatment solution needs significant amount of investment but budgets are tight, which is why, we need planning,\u201d said Jeffrey Sachs, university professor, Columbia University, while speaking at the summit on The Global Water Crisis. What next?.\u000a\u000aSachs expressed concern at India\u2019s intention to double coal production in next few years. He also said that he agrees with India\u2019s minister for new and renewable energy Piyush Goyal who has said that the West needs to pay for their past emissions but cautioned that India needs to ensure that lack of action from West doesn\u2019t become excuse for India to do nothing. He also stressed on need of pricing water.\u000a\u000a\u201cEveryone should have certain amount of water for free, above that amount one needs to pay. By this way, no one will be denied their human right to get adequate water and also, water will be treated as an economic resource,\u201d said Sachs while adding that if you are planning for water, have to plan for it 20-25 years in the future which means looking ahead in a serious way.\u000a\u000aDavid Sedlak, Plato Malozemoff professor, University of California, Berkeley, also stressed on global water crisis and said \u201cwe need to find urban water solutions that are decentralized from bureaucracy\u201d.\u000a\u000a\u201cWorld has gone through three water revolutions and these have happened because of the crisis. Technology has enabled to miniaturize water treatment plants. We need to create networks of self-managed water treatment plants which will help save costs in the long-term. An environmental crisis doesn\u2019t become a crisis unless there is a social movement,\u201d said Sedlak. He also said that, \u201cwhenever we think of water, we think agriculture, but the cities and towns shouldn\u2019t be left out\u201d.\u000a\u000aBoth Sedlak and Sachs also exhorted the global leaders to take decisive action. \u201cOur political leaders are a bunch of irresponsible people with an aim to stay in office, not to make our children safe. We are halfway to what is acknowledged as a dire environmental threat to humanity. Yet we don\u2019t have an action plan. We need global climate action that\u2019s decisive and not just rhetorical,\u201d Sachs added.\u000a\u000aOn India\u2019s ambitious plan of interlinking rivers across the length and breadth of the country, Sedlak said, \u201cthese projects inevitably don\u2019t succeed\u201d.
