VVimal Mishra, meteorologist and assistant professor at IITGandhinagar, was part of a recent committee to investigate the floods at Dhanera in Gujarat. Heavy rains had lashed Gujarat and Rajasthan in July, and the normally quiet Rel river had overflown, causing havoc in the neighbouring areas.As part of a team investigating the impact of this flooding, Mishra looked at the statistics of rainfall and river flows, and compared them with historical figures. In two days, the region had got twice the seasonal total of rainfall, the water level in the river had exceeded 50 times the high water mark. \u201cI was shocked by the numbers,\u201d says Mishra.In his own research, Mishra along with his colleagues was investigating the correlation between extreme meteorological events and climate change . Four years ago, he found that the maximum rainfall was not showing an increase over the last century except in four of 57 towns and cities.In his later work, he showed that extremes are expected to increase over the current century. Specifically, he found that one-to-five-day extreme rains, at levels found once in about 500 years, can increase by about 20-30% over the next century if global warming goes unchecked.If Dhanera in Gujarat set new benchmarks for precipitation, then the role of climate change can\u2019t be ignored in the downpour that drowned Mumbai on August 30. If much of the disaster can be blamed on an inadequate drainage system, sustained changes in weather patterns may have only made it worse. In 24 hours, India\u2019s commercial capital was deluged by 331.4 mm of rain, which claimed lives, flooded roads and swamped railways. As the effects of climate change set in, this may become more commonplace in Mumbai and beyond.Raman Iyer, 80, a retired accountant, has witnessed three natural disasters in Mumbai and believes that as the city gets warmer (and safeguards like mangroves disappear), people will face more of them. \u201cWe thought the 1948 cyclone that hit the city was a once-in-lifetime event, then the flooding happened in 2005 and now this massive rainfall,\u201d he says. \u201cAreas that used to be wetlands and marshes are now glass-and-concrete business districts. The city will heat up and each disaster will be worse than the last.\u201dWith temperatures and emissions rising in India, climate change can cause havoc. \u201cOn a high emissions pathway, the probability of a once-in-a-century flood increases 1,000 times for a city like Kolkata in the latter half of this century,\u201d says Arunabha Ghosh, CEO, Council on Energy, Environment and Water (CEEW), a leading research outfit. \u201cThe probability of intense once-in-30-year floods in the Ganga basin could increase six fold \u2014 that is, it could become once in five years.\u201dSince July 26, 2005, when 944 mm of rain inundated Mumbai, causing unprecedented flooding and loss of lives, the risk of Indian cities from climate change \u2014 and inevitably, poor urban planning \u2014 has been laid bare. Bengaluru, Chennai and Delhi have all weathered natural disasters over the past decade. They could only get worse. While India\u2019s urban decay may be triggering unmanageable flooding across the country, experts believe that climatic vagaries may only increase in frequency and intensity. And, the losses are beginning to mount. According to a recent report submitted by a parliamentary committee to the Ministry of Agriculture, climate change could cause damage of $9-10 billion annually from 2020 to the end of the century.Elsewhere, a study by Tamma Carleton, a researcher at UC Berkeley, said that as many as 59,000 Indian farmers committed suicide over the past three decades due to climate change. \u201cI find\u2026 no evidence that populations within India have been able to successfully adapt to a warming climate,\u201d she says. \u201cThe relationship between temperature and suicide is the same across different populations within India, and at different points in time, suggesting that even as India has gradually warmed while experiencing robust economic growth, people appear no better able to cope with high temperatures.\u201dWhile India may be aggressively chasing its climate change mitigation goals, effects of rising temperatures are beginning to tell on its cities, affecting nature, spreading diseases like dengue and disrupting agriculture. (See Deep Impact).Shweta Srinivasan, senior research analyst at the Centre for Science, Technology & Policy (CSTEP), points out that the Nationally Determined Contributions (NDC) submitted to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) is India\u2019s commitment of tackling climate change in the medium term. \u201cIndia has made rather ambitious announcements\u2026. The 175 GW renewable energy and 40% fossil free electricity capacity target, which at the time of announcement looked difficult, seems much more realisable now,\u201d says Srinivasan. \u201cWe grew from 20 GW renewable energy capacity to 54 GW grid in three to four years. Now, scaling up is key.\u201d Institutional arrangements and uncertainty in terms of financing and project sustainability still need to be addressed.CEEW\u2019s Ghosh points out that while some of these effects may already be felt, the impact may not yet be pinned on climate change. \u201cClimate change is also taking a toll on human health. More than 22,500 deaths have been reported due to heatwaves between 1992 and 2015,\u201d he says. \u201cHowever, this is an under-estimate as death reporting in the country needs to improve. We are experiencing more frequent outbreaks of climate-sensitive diseases such as dengue and malaria.\u201dGiven its large and growing population, increasing carbon dioxide emissions and rising temperatures, India may be precariously placed. According to the Climate Risk Index 2017 by Germanwatch, a nonprofit focused on climate, India was the fourth worst affected due to extreme climatic events in 2015. What\u2019s more, the country ranked No. 2 on the number of deaths due to extreme weather events, as per the same report. While the US Environmental Protection Agency estimates that India is a relatively small contributor of CO2 emissions, globally agriculture contributes 24% of all greenhouse gas emissions. That\u2019s significant in the domestic context, since agriculture employs nearly half of India\u2019s working population and generates under a fifth of its GDP.Already, some organisations are beginning to push farmers in new directions to manage expected vagaries in rainfall and temperature across the country. For example, two hours from Hyderabad, in the arid districts of Mahbubnagar and Anantapur, D Ramachandrudu, director of Watershed Support Services and Activities Network (Wassan), has spent much of the past decade convincing farmers across 50 villages to rethink the way they source and use water. While government-funded watershed programmes help increase water levels, farmers nullify these gains by boring individual wells on their land to feed their crops.Wassan has been pushing farmers to network their borewells and change cropping patterns (from cash to food crops, for example and from water-intensive paddy to millet), to prepare for climate change. On the ground, farmers struggle to deal with uncertain gaps between rainfall (ranging from 20 days to 45 or even 60 days) and lean on artificial irrigation to bridge the gap.With rainfall forecast set to get more erratic with changing climatic patterns, farmers will be compelled to change hardwired habits even faster. \u201cIn this time of climate change, we want to give farmers more equitable access to water,\u201d says Ramachandrudu. \u201cWe have given them a timetable to ease the uncertainties they traditionally faced.\u201d While change may be afoot in agriculture, it may be needed elsewhere, too.\u201cThe aggressive focus on renewables, particularly solar, is right. But that\u2019s about all,\u201d says former Union environment minister Jairam Ramesh. \u201cDealing with climate change goes well beyond solar expansion. The growth trajectory in coal consumption needs a closer look. Forest protection and regeneration have to have an overriding priority.\u201d As India faces up to the widespread effects of climate change, some experts contend that ecological balance and sustainability have to underpin faster economic growth.Ghosh of CEEW says that from a mitigation perspective, India is aggressively pursuing its ambitious renewable energy targets. \u201cIndia\u2019s efforts to support clean energy imply that the share of coal in new capacity will decline compared with what it would have been in the absence of government\u2019s favourable push.\u201d However, with some 40 coal-fired power plants in the works across the country, it remains unclear how these will fit into this energy mix.While India has had an almost decade-long plan to combat climate change, measuring its efficiency remains questionable. \u201cIndia has a National Action Plan on Climate Change, which was released in 2008 and which outlines various missions for action on both mitigation and adaptation. State Action Plans have also been developed,\u201d says Suruchi Bhadwal, an analyst with The Energy Research Institute (TERI). \u201cSince there is no monitoring and evaluation framework, it is very difficult to judge the progress in this regard.\u201dOther missteps may also need to be corrected for India to mitigate risks from climate change. Consider, for example, the seeming diversion of the National Clean Energy and Environment Fund. Set up to fund climate change mitigation initiatives, a move to instead compensate states, following the implementation of GST, is expected to hamper progress on this front. \u201cThe fund could have been used to increase mitigation ambition, and in that sense, it has been a lost opportunity till now,\u201d says Ghosh of CEEW.Others such as Srinivasan of CSTEP contend that the government is mainly using the funds for land acquisition. \u201cA a robust financing architecture for renewables within the GST is required. One possible focus in the short term should be on improving institutional capacity and supporting utilities in buying RE-based power to make clean energy more competitive.\u201dWhile the flood waters receded after 24 hours around Mulund, the Mumbai neighbourhood in which Iyer, the retired accountant, has lived for five decades, he has a simplistic solution to solve Maximum City\u2019s ills. \u201cCancel all construction near mangroves and plant more trees,\u201d he says, supervising the last of the flood water being pumped out of his house. However,, beyond the concrete sprawl of Mumbai, much more needs to be done to deal with climate change.Experts say that India needs to consolidate its clean energy plans by piecing together a coherent long-term strategy to drive production and adoption of this form of power. \u201cMuch of the focus has been on the supply side. However, we also need to determine timebound targets for energy efficiency across end-use sectors, considering most of India\u2019s infrastructure has yet to be built,\u201d says Srinivasan of CSTEP. \u201cSeveral industries in the value chain need to be developed. These include solar cell manufacturing, energy storage devices and smart grid infrastructure.\u201dTo back this up, India needs to beef up its statelevel institutions to execute some of these plans and consider innovative business models (which drove down prices of LED bulbs, for example) to newer areas such as energy storage. As India comes to terms with climate change, it may need several structural shifts to make sure it is prepared for this.For one, a futures commission may help assess new patterns of economic development, drivers and disrupters of strategic and emerging technologies; apart from newer and more robust agreements for renewable energy; state guarantees to reduce counterparty risk, large land banks and innovative financial instruments. Finally, India will need to invest in wider climate risk assessment programmes to keep up with the latest trends in this area. (Climate) change is clearly in the air.A study published in the Journal of Climatology and Forecasting says that wheat yields are expected to decline by 5-10% with every 1C increase in temperature. Overall crop yields could decrease up to 30% in South Asia by the mid-21st century. India could experience a 40% decline in agricultural productivity by the 2080s. Another study, conducted by UC Berkeley Researcher Tamma Carelton and published in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, contends that 59,000 farmer suicides over the past 30 years can be linked to climate change.Rising temperatures can cause more frequent and more severe storms over Indian cities, whose infrastructure has failed to withstand even normal rainfall. More frequent storms, like those that swept Chennai, Mumbai, Bihar and Assam, are expected to hit the country. A single day of lost productivity in Mumbai costs Rs 5,000-6,000 crore. According to a paper by Anup Kanth and Diane Archer from The International Institute for Environment and Development, London, climate change will result in temperature rising by 2-4C, an increase of 7\u201320% in annual precipitation with riverine flooding, cyclones, storm surges and rising sea level.According to a report coauthored by Kristie L Ebi and Joshua Nealon, of the departments of global health and environmental and occupational health sciences, University of Washington, and Sanofi Pasteur\u2019s Asia Pacific epidemiology, respectively, the incidence of dengue has increased 30-fold in the past 50 years, with the disease spreading to higher latitudes (the vector mosquito typically doesn\u2019t survive sub 15 degree C), as temperatures rise.According to researchers at the Indian Institute of Science, Bengaluru, erratic rainfall and rising temperatures are beginning to change the Western Ghats, an ecological hotbed of flora and fauna. As per one report, dense forests with native species have decreased by 2.84%, 4.38% and 5.77% in the northern, central and southern Western Ghats respectively.The Indira Gandhi canal, Rajasthan, has the largest water diversion project in the country. It has played a big role in greening parts of the Thar desert, but it may have had an impact on the climate of the state as well. In recent years, the monsoon has been increasing in intensity in Rajasthan, and some climatologists suspect that diversion of water and large-scale pumping of groundwater are reasons for this. As the earth warms up, India will be one of the hardest hit, as it is in a vulnerable climatic zone. Increasing carbon dioxide is not the only worry for India. Says J Srinivasan, distinguished scientist at the Divecha Centre for Climate Change, IISc: \u201cLocal effects of climate change are more important for a region than global effects.\u201dNo climatologist will make a direct connection between a local event like diversion of water and rainfall over that region, but they are certain that regional changes can have long-term consequences. The Intergovernmental Panel for Climate Change specifies that global effects cannot be measured for areas less than 1 million sq km. What happens over Bengaluru or Mumbai, or Delhi cannot be attributed to increases in carbon dioxide. What we do in these cities have more impact than what the US or China does. Recent research substantiates this.In pic: The Indira Gandhi CanalSubimal Ghosh, associate professor of civil engineering at IIT-Bombay, studied the effect of changing land use patterns over north and northeast India, and the effect of these changes on the monsoon. He found that forests in this region contributed significantly towards rainfall through recycled precipitation. Thick vegetation holds moisture well, this evaporates and comes back as rain. Large amounts of trees have been cut in these region to make way for crops, and there is reason to suppose that this change can affect rainfall over the region.Ghosh studied satellite images and rainfall data, and analysed the correlations. He found that large-scale deforestation is responsible for the declining rainfall around the Gangetic plain and northeast India, and parts of central India. The effect is most pronounced over northeast India. Says Ghosh: \u201cRecycled precipitation is 20-25% of the rain during August and September.\u201d This reduction in recycled moisture is seen to be responsible for early withdrawal of the monsoon over north and northeast India.Similarly, studies have shown an increase in heavy rainfall over cities. \u201cCities are not just concrete,\u201d says Dev Niyogi, professor of agronomy at Purdue University. \u201cThey also have transport and air conditioning and other things.\u201d They store heat during the day and release it at night, creating an urban heat island and making cities hotter by about 3-5 degree Celsius than surrounding areas. \u2014 Hari Pulakkat(Additional reporting by Hari Pulakkat and G Seetharaman)
