VPune: Data from the India Meteorological Department (IMD) revealed majority of monsoons over the past 18 years had been below average like 2017, which ended on a below average note at -5% departure.From 2000, the country has seen as many as 12 monsoons with less rain than the long period average, more so from 2014 to 2017\u2014 a period marked by consecutive monsoons ending on a negative note.According to IMD, a monsoon season is \u201cnormal\u201d when the total rainfall in the country from June to September is within 10% (plus or minus) of the average rain over the long period. Monsoon 2017 for India recently ended with a total rainfall of 841.3mm \u2014 5% less than the average.The rainfall data from 2000 showed despite monsoon being \u201cnormal\u201d in 14 years as per IMD norms, eight of them ended with \u201cnegative rain\u201d or less rainfall than the long period average.A K Sahai, the head of climate research and services at IMD, Pune, told TOI that below-normal or above-normal monsoon seemed to have an epochal periodicity. \u201cThe monsoon rainfall data spanning over the past 100 years or so shows that some 30-year or 40-year period has been marked by positive monsoon rainfall departures while some others had years with below-average rain,\u201d said Sahai.He said the current epoch had more of below-average monsoon seasons. \u201cAccording to the periodicity, above-average monsoon period should have started by now, but there seems to have been a slight delay in that,\u201d said Sahai.Experts stressed there was a possibility of monsoon weakening due to the impact of the climate change, but this was something that researchers were unclear about.\u201cThere is still no clarity on whether the monsoon will intensify or weaken due to the impact of the climate change. One thing is clear that extreme rainfall events may increase due to the climate change, which may reduce the number of rainy days in India,\u201d said Sahai.A K Srivastava, the head of IMD\u2019s climate monitoring and analysis group, Pune, said, \u201cThe current epoch \u2014 from 1991 to 2020 \u2014 has shown a trend of negative or low rainfall. Past statistics show the epochal behaviour of monsoon, but how long will this rainall trend continues beyond the year 2020 cannot be gauged.\u201d
