VHYDERABAD: The Telangana government and GHMC must adopt the Surat model to build a resilient city given an increase in erratic rainfall leading to flooding of colonies . This was suggested by urban studies experts at the Administrative Staff College of India (ASCI), who are also pushing for separate town planning and building permission rules for low-lying and flood-prone areas .Surat has floated a publicprivate trust, headed by a chief resilient officer, to coordinate with various wings of the municipal corporation regarding flooding and water management. \u201cAlmost all Indian cities are witnessing urban flooding due to high intensity rainfall in short periods. Governments need to start building resilient cities that can withstand the shocks of climate change. Like seismic zones , cities should mark flooding zones and building rules should be changed accordingly. Rain water harvesting should also be taken up on a big scale. The Surat model can be customised to suit the needs of Hyderabad,\u201c Prof V Srinivas Chary , ASCI director of urban program, told TOI.Surat, a city with one of the highest per capita income, has witnessed 25 notable floods in 100 years. Of these, eight to nine were in the last 20 years itself. \u201cTwo historic events, the 1994 plague and the 2006 floods, which caused a loss of $2 billion, made the corporation fight back. In 2009, Surat was selected for the Asian cities resilient network for climate change. Later, a multistakeholder trust was formed to study various aspects of urban flooding, water supply , environment and its impact on health," Kamlesh Yagnik, Su rat's chief resilient officer told TOI over phone.The UK-based Rockefeller Foundation chose Surat to be part of 100 resilient global cities. \u201cThe authorities later relocated at least 50,000 families from encroached areas into new buildings,\u201c said Yagnik.GHMC officials feel they face a peculiar situation regarding grant of building approvals. \u201cAs per rules, building permission can be granted in 30 days. But we have a lot of pressure to grant it early. With limited staff, processing and checking the facts on the ground is difficult. We will study the Surat model and check if it can be applied to the city . Hyderabad has been witnessing 8-10 cm rain in a span of oneand-half hour. We need Rs 12,000 crore to clear encroachments on nalas. Last October, we demolished 800 structures soon after the floods, but legal cases followed. This time, we have served notices on 1,000 structures. We have filed a caveat to stop litigation,\u201c GHMC commissioner B Janardhan Reddy told TOI.
