VDemonetisation and GST may have had a positive and negative impact on the Indian economy, but no one would have thought that reducing India\u2019s carbon emissions growth would be one of its benefits. Yet, that was one of the major fallouts of the combo regulation, even as global carbon emissions continued to grow this year.Scientists think that India\u2019s emissions will pick up with economic growth in a year or two, and thus put pressure on other countries to reduce their share even further.Global carbon dioxide emissions growth had slowed down in the last three years, giving hope to environmentalists and policymakers around the world that the Paris Climate Agreement might work. But it picked up again this year, as a widely discussed paper in the journal Environment Research Letters showed two days ago. The growth has come mainly from China, which had gone back to using more coal in its power plants. \u201cTime is running out on our ability to keep global temperature increases below 2 Centigrade and,\u201d the authors of the paper wrote, \u201ceven more immediately, anything close to 1.5 Centigrade.\u201dThe research paper and a series of other papers and announcements have coincided with the climate talks in Bonn this week. This annual United Nations conference has continued where the Paris conference left off, looking at where countries have not kept up to their promises in Paris.In the last year, global carbon dioxide emissions had increased by around 36 gigatonnes, and this level had remained roughly steady over the last three years.Although the rate was still high, environmental scientists and policymakers have been pleased at the plateau in the rate of increase. The consensus was that the rate of increase will remain steady and start going down soon. This year\u2019s expected increase of 2% over last year, driven by China, shows that a decrease may not happen soon. \u201cTrends in China are such a big part of the global story,\u201d says Navroz Dubash, senior fellow of the Centre for Policy Research in Delhi.The alarm among some scientists is because of the limited carbon budget available for the world to keep temperature increases to below 2 Centigrade. Many scientists think that temperature increases above this level can cause runaway effects that are difficult or impossible to control. Although 2 Centigrade is an arbitrary number, uncertainties in modelling increase rapidly after this temperature, which was why scientists largely think of it as a limit.At current levels of increase, the world will use up the carbon budget to keep temperature increase down to below 2 Centigrade within 15 years. The more carbon budget we use up every year, the less time we have to keep the temperatures to below the 2 C number. This is why the projected increase in the rate of emissions has so worried the scientists. But not everyone is alarmed at the moment.\u201cThe emission rate will go up and down for some time,\u201d says J Srinivasan, distinguished scientist at the Divecha Centre for Climate Change at the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) in Bangalore, \u201cBut my view is that the global carbon dioxide emissions are stabilising.\u201dIn his view, the world is at an inflection point in the way it uses energy, but it is not easy to predict how long it will take for the emissions to start coming down. Most developed countries have stabilised in their emissions, and have started showing a decrease. China, the world\u2019s largest emitter, may have some way to go before stabilisation. India, still some distance away from being a developed country, will take even longer.As the country soon with the largest population, India is a key player in keeping global temperature down. \u201cThe heat is off India at the moment,\u201d says Dubash. \u201cBut it will come back.\u201d(Global CO2 emissions from fossil-fuel use and industry (open circles) and gross world product expressed as purchasing power parity since 1990. Numbers for 2017 are projections.)(From top to bottom: Relative to year 2000, gross domestic product, global CO2 emissions from fossil-fuel use and industry, global energy use, CO2 intensity of the energy system (global CO2 emissions from fossil-fuel use and industry divided by global energy use), and energy intensity of the global economy (global energy use divided by global GDP) from 1990\u20132017)Burning of fossil fuels and industry together contribute nearly 90% of the global emissions, with deforestation and land degradation contributing the rest. When taken by sectors, industry contributes 21% of the emissions. A report four months ago from the nonprofit Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP) showed that 70% of the emissions from 1998 are from just 100 large companies. Global emissions will decrease significantly if a few thousand large corporations cut their carbon footprint. So far, their efforts are not significant enough, according to CDP.Of the 1,839 high-impact companies identified by CDP, around 1,000 started disclosing their carbon emissions. Of these, only 14% have set targets for themselves, and very few have goals consistent with the Paris Agreement. Among the high-impact companies, 61 are in India, and 23 disclose their carbon emissions. No one is Paris-compliant. \u201cCompanies are doing something,\u201d says Damandeep Singh, CDP director, India. \u201cBut it is nowhere near enough.\u201dOf late, global emission of methane has been rising, and scientists have not figured out all the reasons. This gas is 30 times more powerful than carbon dioxide in its heat-trapping potential, and is produced from both natural and human sources. Agriculture and dairy farming are the most significant human sources of methane while wetlands and oceans form the natural sources.Many scientists fear that rising temperatures can cause methane to escape from sources where it is buried at the moment, causing runaway global warming So they are watching methane emissions closely, but do not know where the increase is coming from. \u201cAt this moment we cannot untangle the natural from the human sources of methane,\u201d says Anita Ganesan, lecturer at the School of Geographical Sciences at the University of Bristol. A few months ago, Ganesan had shown that methane emissions from India were not rising.Although the news is not good overall, many scientists are hopeful of a slowdown in the greenhouse gas emissions growth and their eventual decline. Forests form an important part of the future methods to control emissions.Large-scale deforestation caused forests to emit carbon in the 1980s, but this trend seemed to have turned around at the moment.Although tropical forests are still being destroyed, the global story is not bad. \u201cThe rate of deforestation has slowed down at a global scale,\u201d says Govindasamy Bala, professor at the Centre for Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences in IISc.\u201cNow forests are a net sink for carbon.\u201d While how this happens has not been directly measured, scientists think that now forests can take in up to 30% of the carbon that is being emitted. And can take more. Which is where remedial action can begin immediately.
