VSHIMLA: Himachal Pradesh is facing impacts of climate change as temperatures are rising and rainfall as well as snowfall are becoming erratic, affecting agriculture, horticulture and livelihoods. Most weather stations in Himachal Pradesh and Jammu and Kashmir are facing increasing trend of temperature in the last three decades.Giving an overview of changing weather patterns in Himachal Pradesh, director of Shimla Meteorological Centre Dr Manmohan Singh said monsoon in state was expanding but overall rainfall was on a decline. He added that most weather stations were reporting increasing trends in temperature in Himachal Pradesh as well as Jammu and Kashmir in the past 30 years. He added that snowfall days in Srinagar and Shimla were showing a decreasing trend.Senior scientific officer at Himachal Pradesh Council of Science and Technology Dr S S Randhawa said glaciers were direct indicators of climate change. \u201cIn Spiti valley, deglaciation has been to the extent of 10-12% during 2001 and 2007. The rate of retreat of glaciers in Baspa and Parvati basins has also been fast since 1962, in some cases as high as 172 meters per year. Area under snow cover too has changed between October to June in six basins,\u201d he added.Randhawa said decline in snow cover ranges between 5-37% in 2010- 2014 period as compared to 2015 and 2016. The number of lakes formed with water melted from glaciers and also due to landslides too is going up with 116 lakes in 2013 to 192 in 2015 in the Chenab basin, he added.Prof S K Bhardwaj from Dr Y S Parmar University of Horticulture and Forestry in Solan said climate change was affecting quality as well as yield of apple crop. With this, farmers of the hill state had started growing other fruits such as pomegranate and even vegetables like cabbage in apple orchards, he added.
