VPUNE: The sharp and sudden drop in temperature in the second week of February has caused damage to grape and banana cultivations and vegetable crop in Nashik, Pune, Aurangabad and Osmanabad districts.\u000a\u000aPlantations and crops on 1,689 hectares in the four districts have reported more than 50% damage. Grape farms on 34 hectares have also been adversely affected including cracking of grape beads. This has been revealed in an analysis report of the state horticulture department.\u000a\u000aPlantations and crops on 20,775 hectares have reported less than 50% damage, of which 1,913 hectares are under grape cultivation, said D G Bakwad, director, state horticulture department.\u000a\u000a"The temperature dropped by about 8 degrees celsius to 2.8 degrees celsius in Nashik district last Thursday. Jalgaon, which is the largest banana-producing district in the country, also recorded a sudden drop in temperature affecting banana plantations that will result in lower yields\u000a\u000a," he added.\u000a\u000aGrape is an important crop in the state that gives higher returns to farmers.\u000a\u000aThe grape export market in Maharashtra is worth more than Rs 500 crore, hence farmers are more concerned about damage\u000a\u000as to grape farms\u000a\u000a.\u000a\u000aBakwad said, "It was so cold that most grape bunches developed cracks and farmers lost the plants. The leaves, which prepare food through photosynthesis, were damaged so badly that the photosynthesis procedure could not take place and the plant cannot produce grapes now. It is the same with banana plantations and other vegetables, where leaves have been badly damaged affecting the yield from the farm."\u000a\u000aThe temperature continued to be low for the next couple of days and the area suffering damage to crops increased in these districts. Compared to vegetables, investment in grape farms runs in lakhs and hence the loss due to damage is also high\u000a\u000a. One hectare of grape plantation needs investment of Rs 1 crore and above including cost of iron rods, cables, saplings, fertilisers, pesticides and human labour\u000a\u000a.Bakwad said, "A report would be submitted to the state agriculture department for further action. Temperature is expected to fall in the coming days, according to the weather department. If it happens, there will be more damage to these crops. Though farmers cover the compound wall of grapes with old saris to maintain some warmth, it is not a reliable method."
