VPowering the iPad with solar energy in sun-starved Antarctica is a breeze. But as Paras Loomba \u2013 a 26-year-old engineer from Ferozepur who was the 'Mr Fix It' in this year's 70-member International Antarctic Expedition \u2013 would tell you, using numb fingers to maneuver the screen at sub-zero temperatures is a different ball game altogether.Working in minus 3 degrees Celsius with penguins and humpback whales for company, Loomba lit up the entire base in Antarctica solely with renewable energy. Chosen among hundreds all over the world, Loomba was one of just four Indians among the team headed to the earth's coldest, windiest, driest and remotest continent.As the only hands-on engineer and the only techie in the team, it was up to him to lug all the equipment \u2013 wires, panels and transistors. These he would use to harness renewable energy to run almost everything, from lanterns to mikes to the latest drool-worthy gadget."If I can play Angry Birds in Antarctica using only solar power , there is no reason why Siachen can't work on clean tech," Loomba says. Of course, it meant sacrificing thermal gear for equipment that took up more than half of his permitted 29 kg luggage."The best part was that all these global leaders (on the expedition) were witnessing Indian technology lighting up the Antarctic. Imagine what wonders this can do for our forces," adds Loomba. The annual expedition was led by Sir Robert Swan, the only polar explorer to have trekked North and South Poles, and comprised environmentalists, motivational speakers and corporate executives including three from India.The annual expedition aims to show a cross section of society the effects of climate change first hand, so that they could be inspired to take small committed steps in their personal life to help lower global carbon footprint. Unique to this year's expedition was the use of Indian-made solar lanterns at the campsites. "My mom used one of the lamps, recharged in Antarctica, for a whole month at home," Loomba says. In fact, Swan's base camp is the only renewable energypowered camp in the world.The group also recorded alarming changes in temperatures in this ecosensitive region, blamed on climate change. For instance, whereas the team expected near-nil humidity, their instruments recorded a staggering 5%. Loomba says acute effects of climate change are seen clearly at the Poles."The ice cover in the Arctic region is actually increasing whereas in Antarctica we saw a huge 200 metre ice shelf \u2013 that is twice the length of a football stadium \u2013 break into the water, all because of rising global temperatures," he says.Though every team member was aware of the effects of global climate change, the truth hit them hard when they witnessed the drastic effects themselves. "Getting pictures clicked with hump-backed whales was our moment of reckoning. It hit us hard." These large, warm-blooded mammals traditionally stayed away from the ice-cold waters of the southern ocean. But rising temperatures and melting icebergs now make the waters navigable to these whales.Loomba believes that Antarctica is a must visit for every person once in their lifetime for a lesson in humility as nature's grandeur takes over. "But at this pace of change, the place will be lost before people can truly experience its magnificence," he says.
