VThe Centre for Science and Environment recently released the findings of a study it had undertaken to examine the impact of climate change on development in the Sundarbans. The following facts have since become a part of the public domain: I. The sea surface temperature (SST) in these islands has been increasing at 0.5 degree centigrade per decade. II. In the last 25 years, the sea level has risen at a rate of 8 mm per year. This is more than double the global average. III. The monsoon has become erratic but intense, and incidents of severe cyclones have risen by 26 per cent over the Bay of Bengal. IV. Between the years 2000 and 2008, the Sundarbans witnessed a net soil loss of 44.042 sq km annually. V. Soil salinity in the northern Sundarbans stands at up to 8 parts per thousand. In the south, it ranges between 8-20 PPT (the safety limit being 4-6 PPT). Now consider some of the other findings that can help to map the contours of the challenge of development in the Sundarbans: I. Nearly 44 per cent of the Sundarbans population lives below the poverty line, and 65 per cent of the total working population is dependent on agriculture. II. Approximately 87 per cent of the population suffers from food scarcity, while the average holding of cultivable land per agricultural labourer is less than 0.5 hectares. III. Healthcare facilities are primitive. There is just one technical college in an area as large as 250 sq km. The disaster management system is equally archaic. A scrutiny of these facts establishes the link between deteriorating ecological conditions and the concomitant slide in the development graph of the Sundarbans. The CSE report indicates that the rise in SST has had a negative impact on rainfall, which, in turn, has adversely affected agriculture. Changing sea temperatures have also led to the dwindling of some fish species, the Indian mackerel for example, and made fishing less profitable. Rising sea levels have aggravated soil erosion, inundation and, consequently, salinity, affecting paddy production. (The yield of paddy in the Sundarbans is 1.5-2 tonnes per hectare, as against the national average of 3.28 tonnes.) The fall in agricultural productivity, combined with the lack of alternative livelihoods and the depletion of non-timber forest products, has led to a sharp rise in migration. A survey by the Jayaprakash Institute of Social Change, conducted between September 2010 and January 2011, cited by the CSE report, showed that 75 per cent of the respondents families had witnessed out-migration. (The picture on top is of a boat abandoned by a migrant family.) But the Bengal governments inability to understand such evident links has resulted in ecology and climate change being perceived as unconnected to development at the policy level. Significantly, a holistic view of the ecological crisis is seldom represented  the full-page advertisements listing the achievements of the current government, brought out on its completion of one year in office, referred only to water conservation. Moreover, the complexity of the Sundarbans ecology and the need to forge adaptation tools at the local level remain unacknowledged. For instance, during her visit to Gosaba in January, the chief minister, Mamata Banerjee, requested the locals to give up their land for the construction of stronger embankments. One wonders whether the chief minister is aware that embankments, while partially resisting erosion, have increased the deposit of sediments on the river bed, raising the water level and, ironically, the possibility of flooding. My third visit to the Sundarbans  this time I went as far as Emilybari  was not undertaken to contest the CSEs findings. Many of the symptoms of the unfolding ecological crisis have remained the same since my first visit after Aila. The saline top soil remains yellow on vast stretches of paddy fields in Rangabelia and Satjelia (bottom centre). On the kheyaghat at Jatirampur, I was shown some green coconuts that had developed brown gashes because of water contamination (bottom left). On my way to Emilybari, I discovered that the leaves of the Kalo Bain (Avicennia marina)  a mangrove species  had turned crimson on account of the waters high acidic content (bottom right). I wanted to find out, on this visit, whether the people of the Sundarbans had in their mind a template that could force the government to co-opt ecology, though belatedly, into the debate on development. So imagine my surprise when I heard the panchayat pradhan of Emilybari elaborate, not on the ecological challenges, but on the beautification drive being undertaken in the village. The serpentine and unmetalled road that led to the river would be lit with solar lamps (there is no electricity in Emilybari); trees like Shonajhuri and Eucalyptus  not the threatened but immensely useful Hargaj (Acanthus ilicifolius) or Kalo Bain  would be planted. Pressed further, he conceded that the plan to introduce solar lamps was an exercise in populism. He added that the forest department, in its afforestation drive, had dismissed his plea for including mangrove species that resist soil erosion and act as a buffer during cyclones. The pradhans helpless attempts at sensitizing the local administration to these ecological needs are indicative of three crucial things. First, as argued by the CSE report, climate change and the consequent ecological degradation in the Sundarbans remain unrepresented at local policy and institutional levels. Second, the adaptation techniques that are being devised are flawed and ineffective because of a rudimentary understanding of the ecological transformations. The inhabitants of Emilybari confessed to the administrations tacit support to migration as a tool to contend with the crisis. Finally, these grim realities underscore the urgent need to decentralize grassroots institutions like panchayats and gram sabhas. However, decentralization is unlikely within the existing political framework on account of two reasons. Political parties are willing to view panchayats only as conduits to securing power. The autonomy of panchayats has also been severely compromised by the entrenched elitism in the bureaucracy. (A forest department official, even though an outsider, has the temerity to instruct the pradhan, a man with a far better understanding of the areas fragile ecology, on what saplings should be planted in Emilybari.) What must be explored is the possibility of amending the laws to facilitate the creation of an apolitical, but constitutional, apparatus that can act as an agency in tandem with the panchayats to exert pressure on the State to combine ecological and developmental concerns. The people I talked to in Emilybari seemed to be amenable to the creation of advisory committees within the local governance model. Unlike the panchayats, the advisory bodies made up of independent experts would not be saddled with political responsibilities. This would give them the leverage necessary to engage with the insensitivities of the State without compromising the authority of the panchayats. But the inclusion of ecology in the framework of development would also require the immediate stakeholders  the people of the Sundarbans  to transform themselves into an effective pressure group. This is certainly a risky proposition in a country that has ceded the middle ground for dialogue between the State and dissidents. But one should examine the option of exploring policy initiatives such as the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act as a means of imposing an ecological agenda on elected representatives. The CSE report has legitimately expressed reservations about the MNREGA as an effective agency to raise awareness on ecology and development. This is because the MNREGA has been crippled by persistent deficiencies: discrimination on political lines in the distribution of job cards, the States inability to pay compensation on time, an embedded orthodoxy that has prevented planners from using the MNREGA to make community assets ecologically viable. While sharing the CSEs cynicism, I would like to argue that the MNREGA still remains the best bet for local communities to demand cogent, inclusive safeguards for the ecology that would also hasten development. This is not only because the MNREGA has a phenomenal reach (even remote corners of the country are aware of the 100-day work initiative), but also because, as a policy, it has occasionally shown glimpses of flexibility. This month, a notification by the ministry of rural development amended the MNREGAs schedules to include the creation of personal assets  building of poultry shelters or latrines  as eligible for payment. Similarly, in the Sundarbans, the scope of the enlisted tasks under this welfare programme can be widened to include the desilting of rivers and the cutting of channels in them to check erosion and afforestation. Local communities must also be allowed to contribute not only labour but also the fruit of their intricate knowledge of the Sundarbans ecology. The government must stop looking at the MNREGA only as a means of economic sustenance. The local community and its representatives, such as the panchayats, must also be taught to demand the incorporation of sound ecological practices within the ambit of this Central programme. I have often wondered why the definition of the stakeholders as victims of climate change in the Sundarbans excludes Calcuttans. The citys creaking infrastructure is being put under pressure by migrants, who provide cheap domestic labour. Perhaps it is time for Calcuttans to ponder whether they ought to make their own the battle against the ravages of nature in the Sundarbans. Admittedly, this can only be fostered by greater interaction between the city dwellers and the islanders. Tourists, who flock to these mesmerizing islands, could be the primary targets for raising levels of awareness. On an earlier visit, I remember a group of tourists listening attentively to the guide  a local who, after pointing to the dead trunk of a Sundari tree (Heritiera fomes) floating on the river, said that the islands derived their name from that species. He should have added that the Sundari is a rare sight today, even in the forests. The CSE report notes that the outbreak of agamora and the rise of salinity have depleted the Sundaris numbers. Tour operators should be requested  or even hired  by NGOs to lead tourists to not just the Sajnekhali watch-tower but also to the interiors of Gosaba, Bali, Satjelia, Rangabelia in order to gain direct knowledge of the looming ecological crisis. I would like to suggest that tourists should take the land route to observe how the predatory rivers are devouring the land, washing away feeble embankments, poisoning the fields, even as the foliage wilts, fruits wither and the conflict between humans and animals intensifies. Hopefully, after witnessing such disturbing scenes, Calcuttans, who remain largely indifferent to the plight of the islands and their people, would demand corrective action from the government more stridently. On this trip, while crossing the Bidya river, I witnessed a tourist taking pictures of the dusk falling. A young woman in her bridal wear sat with her husband near him. The skin on their arms, having been exposed to saline water, had developed white patches. But the camera, I noticed, remained focused on the darkening sky.
