VThe unseasonal rain that has begun to fall on Karnataka every January and February hasn\u2019t affected coffee production very much \u2014 there\u2019s just a 5% dip in yield. But, it\u2019s entirely possible there will be discernible change in the quality of the coffee bean... and the coffee that you drink.Blame global warming ? There\u2019s more.Assam, which accounts for more than half (52 per cent) of all the tea India produces , last year grew 15 million kg less than the year before. Some of the tea reportedly tasted different \u2014 much weaker than the \u201cstrong\u201d brew that Assam is famous for.And then there is Himachal Pradesh\u2019s main crop \u2014 the apple. The fruit grows on 90,000 hectares across the state but Himachal could lose as much as 25 per cent of that, as low-lying orchards at anywhere between 4,000 and 5,500 ft start to warm up.A CHANGE OF TASTEAcross India \u2014 from east to west, south to north \u2014 the effects of climate change are seen to be slowly becoming apparent. Karnataka coffee, Assamese tea and Himachal apples are just three on a lengthening list of crops that are affected by changing climate patterns. Maharashtra\u2019s grapes, Goa\u2019s mangoes and cashew nuts, Kerala's paddy crops and Haryana\u2019s wheat \u2014 are seen to be affected too.It\u2019s part of a change that is sweeping the globe, which the United Nations \u2019 Food and Agricultural Organization took note of in September. At the time, the agency's assistant director general, Hafez Ghanem, predicted a turbulent long-term outlook for food prices across the world because of more frequent extreme weather due to climate change.So what, if anything, is India doing about some of its key crops?RAINING TROUBLEDown south, the Coffee Board of India has begun a special insurance scheme to help farmers cope but it admits it might find it hard to cushion them against the impact of sharply falling exports. Karnataka coffee is sent to Italy, Russia, France, Germany and the UK and Jayarama, the Coffee Board\u2019s director of research , says these markets may be put off by the declining quality of the coffee.This, because coffee is acutely sensitive to rainfall and badly needs the blossom shower in the flowering season \u2014 mid-March \u2014 and the backing shower \u2014 roughly three weeks after that. This is crucial to bean development. Jayarama says the problem is the additional showers in January and February, which cause \u201cthe coffee crop to fruit twice or maybe three times.\u201d The beans that come later, he adds, are inferior.If Karnataka\u2019s coffee-growers have it bad, so do the Nashik Valley\u2019s grape farmers. They\u2019ve had to start tweaking cultivation cycles \u2014 the fruit is grown across 1,80,000 hectares in Maharashtra \u2014 because of changing weather patterns.Mahendra Sahir, president of the Maharashtra State Grape Growers Association, says the state has received rain in November for the last three to four years. It\u2019s forced farmers to delay pruning and \u201cif pruning is delayed, everything that comes afterwards is also delayed,\u201d says Sahir. He acknowledges that times are increasingly hard and \u201csometimes we find it difficult to meet our deadline for the supply of grapes to the port, from where the fruit is sent on to European Union (EU) countries.\u201dCLIMATE CHAOSUp in the northeast of India meanwhile, scientists are gloomily predicting the region will become wetter. So what is going on? The only thing scientists seem able to agree on is that there is no agreement on climate change affecting crop patterns.Dr H Pathak, principal investigator of the Indian Agricultural Research Institute\u2019s Climate Change Challenge Programme, says the definite change in rainfall patterns could lead to our worst-case scenario. \u201cGlobal warming doesn\u2019t only mean a rise in average temperatures. It\u2019s a little more complicated than that. There is for example also a rise in CO2 and a change in rainfall patterns, which could affect India very severely because much of our agriculture is still rainfed . Without rain, it will be impossible to grow many crops.\u201dBut B P Yadav, director of the Indian Meteorological Department, points out that picture is not clear cut at all. The number of days of light rainfall has decreased, but the number of days of heavy rainfall has increased, he points out. Taken together, the total quantum of rainfall has remained unchanged.ON THE BOILThere is a genuine sense of helplessness about it all. At December's annual general meeting of the Tea Association of India, its president D P Maheshwari announced: \u201cThe incessant rain, followed by a severe attacks of pests \u2014 mainly helopeltis, the tea bug mosquito which feeds on the tea leaf \u2014 caused a huge loss of crop in 2010.\u201dThe Tea Association president estimates that some tea gardens suffered crop losses of as much as 20 to 30% on the previous year's output. Soon after the disappointing yields came in, local planters started to report that the taste of Assam tea had also changed. The implications are frightening. Assam tea earns 50% of India's Rs 9,000 crore income from tea sales and a change in its signature taste could mean a rapid drop in demand.Cue sunny Goa, down in the west of India.Last year, it rained for 10 months, only letting up in February and March. Goa\u2019s two major crops \u2014 mango and cashew \u2014 were badly hit. Again, the implications are horrendous . Goa produces 40 metric tonnes of mangoes and 24 metric tonnes of cashews. A local farmer complains of enormous \u201cconcern about the extension of the rainy season and temperature fluctuations during the season.\u201dPESKY PESTSThe changing rainfall pattern also threatens Kerala\u2019s paddy crop. The sowing season runs from October to December but in Kuttanad, which is justly called the state\u2019s rice bowl, the incessant rain meant sowing could only begin in December. A changed cultivation cycle means pests attack the crop at a different stage of growth. It\u2019s meant that insects like the rice thrips, earlier thought of as minor pests, are destroying vast swathes of the crop in Kuttanad.S Leenakumari of the Rice Research Station in Mankombu in Alappuzha district, admits the situation is dire. \u201cThis could trigger a panic, forcing farmers to take to insecticides, which in turn will also kill the pest\u2019s naturally-occurring enemies. That will finally lead to insecticide dependence in the long run,\u201d he says.Kerala\u2019s rice farmers are in a bind. Delay the sowing season and the flowering season gets pushed back, probably to the summer. But if daytime temperatures cross 35 degrees, there is a severe danger the heat will shrivel the grains and production will fall.This has already been noticed in Palakkad \u2014 the state\u2019s other major paddy-growing area where daytime temperatures can cross 45 degrees in summer.STAPLE STORYIndia\u2019s other staple grain \u2014 wheat \u2014 is also affected. Dr Pathak of the Indian Agricultural Research Institute\u2019s Climate Change Challenge Programme, says that \u201csince 2002, a phenomenon called \u2018terminal heat\u2019 , caused by global warming, has been observed in the months of February and March.\u201dThat\u2019s a crucial period for a wheat crop because that's when it begins to mature. A sudden rise in temperature causes the grain to shrivel and production to fall.Up in the mountains of Himachal Pradesh, meanwhile, the battle is on to save the primacy of its apple crop. Apples need at least 900 to 1,100 hours at temperatures below seven degrees celsius if they are to ripen properly. But experts say if the state warms up too much the apples will grow faster and be a lot less tasty. S P Bharadwaj of the Dr Y S Parmar University of Horticulture and Forestry in Nauni says rising temperatures will not just lower the fruit\u2019s shelf life, it will make them less juicy and a lot less crunchy.Experts say Himachal\u2019s apple growers need to change with the times \u2014 and the climate \u2014 growing different varieties, including those better suited to warmer temperatures and using techniques like drip irrigation.But it may not be so easy for everyone to change with the times \u2014 and the climate.Reports by Jayashree Nandi in Bengaluru, Naresh Mitra in Guwahati, Nikhil Deshmukh in Pune, Paul Fernandes in Goa, Vijay Sabharwal in Kurukshetra , Ananthakrishnan G in Thiruvananthapuram and Jagdish Bhatt in Shimla
