VWith several Nationalist Congress Party (NCP) Ministers in the limelight for all the wrong reasons, Minister of State for Rural Development Jayant Patil is trying to make a difference in Maharashtra.\u000a\u000aDivested of the Finance portfolio, which went to Deputy Chief Minister Ajit Pawar, Mr. Patil has embarked on an ambitious programme of tree-planting and rural sanitation, combined with the planned development of villages for the first time.\u000a\u000aHe has visited nearly half of his scheduled 120 grama sabhas to promote the \u2018eco-village programme,' which could cost the State Rs. .450 crore. While no fresh doles were being handed out to people, they had to fulfil certain criteria to be eligible for funds under the programme, which was launched on October 2, 2010. The response has been overwhelming, going by the large turnout at the meetings, according to Mr. Patil.\u000a\u000aTo qualify under the programme, each village must achieve the target of \u201cone person, one tree,\u201d at least 60 per cent of the families must build toilets and avoid open defecation, and tax collection should be around 60 per cent. About 14,000 gram panchayats are set to qualify for the programme and funds would be allotted for further development according to the size of the population. The formula is simple \u2014 \u201cThink globally, act locally.\u201d Each person in the village must plant at least one tree. Mr. Patil's interactive speeches abound with climate change references, humourous appeals to build toilets; and the audience has been responsive. In an interview during his hectic travels, Mr. Patil told The Hindu that he had called a meeting, last February, of all the chief executive officers of the zilla parishads before a government resolution was drafted for the programme.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe decided to gear up the machinery to make saplings available in a planned way and also evolved a system of reporting from the gram panchayat-level to the deputy secretary-level. The tree-planting reports were good initially and now, in 19,000 gram panchayats (of the total 27,920), it has been highly successful,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aGram panchayats with a population of less than 1,000 would be eligible for Rs.2 lakh every year for three years. Those with a population of more than 1,000 would get Rs.3 lakh, and so on. Larger gram panchayats would be entitled to funds between Rs.15 lakh and Rs.30 lakh over three years. This money could be spent under 12 heads \u2014 including building roads, gutters, waste management or sewage treatment and disposal systems, and street lighting using solar or CFL. There was a system of verification to make sure the villages had qualified and there was a committee of zilla parishad CEOs, panchayat Samiti committees and a State-level committee headed by the Minister.\u000a\u000aThe eco-village concept has another dimension. Villages with over 5,000 people can go in for a development plan similar to that of cities, which will be valid for 20 years. The Environment Department and the Maharashtra Pollution Control Board (MPCB) have shortlisted about 20 consultants, NGOs and organisations which would be trained in preparing a uniform template for the eco-village planning, according to Environment Secretary Valsa Nair Singh.
