VNEW DELHI: South Africa is all set to kick off its preparations for the year-end UN climate change conference at Durban. Environment ministers from countries representing the entire spectrum of interests in the climate process will be meeting in Berlin for the Petersberg Climate Dialogue. The first major ministerial meeting, since the Cancun climate conference, aims to identify the deliverables at Durban and build the political environment required to push the process through.As with the first Petersberg Dialogue held last year, the July 3-4 ministerial is the joint initiative of the Germany and incoming presidency of the Conference of Parties. Last year's meet chaired by Germany and Mexico, in the aftermath of the Copenhagen conference, focused on ways to rebuild trust and identify areas of co-operation. This year the attempt is to create the political momentum to address the crucial issues such as ambition, equity, sources for long-term funding.This exercise gains importance as consensus has already been built on low-hanging fruits of the climate negotiation process as reflected in the Cancun Agreements. The Durban conference will therefore have to focus on the politically more contentious issues such as the fate of the Kyoto Protocol, level of ambition to reduce emissions, identifying sources for long-term finance. The Petersberg Dialogue, chaired by German Environment Minister Norbert Rottgen and South African Minister Maite Nkoana-Mashabane, will aim to identify evolve a framework to address these issues.At the Berlin ministerial, South Africa hopes to work out the contours of what could be a "balanced and credible" Durban outcome. This will involve discussions on the fate of the second commitment period for the Kyoto protocol, the raising of ambition in dealing with climate change, making the Green Climate Fund operational, especially resolving the question of sources for long-term financing for climate change, and the technology mechanism.Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh, who is attending the ministerial, will lead the discussions along with UK Environment Minister Chris Huhne on the policy options and key issues that need to be resolved, and the elements of a Durban outcome.The prospect of a second commitment period for the Kyoto Protocol and identifying sources for long-term finance for climate change are key issues that would dominate the meet. The focus on these issues is expected as South Africa seeks to use the opportunity accorded by the UN climate conference to establish itself as the leader of the African continent.Both these issues are of crucial concern to the African Group. These concerns are supported by the BASIC countries, of which South Africa is a constituent. The BASIC has made it clear that it will play an active role in shaping the Durban conference.
