VNEW DELHI: The effort to ensure long-term financing to address climate change is expected to be a key issue at the year-end UN climate conference to be held at Durban in South Africa. At Cancun, it was agreed that a climate fund would be set up and South Africa would like to make sure that it is operationalised at the Durban conference. A crucial issue that needs to be addressed is that of sourcing long-term finance. This is an area on which there has been little discussion, especially at the decision-making level.South Africa is keen to ensure that a decision on sources of long-term finance is agreed to at the Durban Conference. African countries are mostly classified as net recipients of climate related finance. To this end, South Africa plans to begin discussions on the issue at the Petersberg dialogue to be held in the first week of July in Germany. It is understood to have reached out to Germany to help bring the vexed issue of sources for long-term finance on the political agenda. South Africa also proposes to hold a ministerial in the run up to Durban which will deal with this issue.Consensus on the question of sources could prove to be a difficult task. There is little agreement among countries about which sources need to be tapped. A decision in Durban would aid South Africa\u2019s effort to position itself within the broader African political spectrum. The Africa group has already made a submission on the issue, stressing that a burden sharing mechanism, including assessed contribution, needs to be established to identify flows of financial support.There is a great deal of opposition and unease on a levy on aviation and maritime traffic, which among the sources that is under consideration. The European Union\u2019s decision to make all airlines flying into or through Europe for their pollution by bringing aviation within the ambit of the emission trading scheme has already met with opposition The United States and China are opposed to the move, with Beijing going so far as to put on hold its multibillion dollar order for 10 Airbus aircrafts.India too has opposed a levy on aviation and maritime traffic as it would blur the principle of common but differentiated responsibilities on which the UN convention is based. Developed countries are required to provide finances to the developing countries. The issue of long-term finance has received little attention at the decision making level. In part this can be attributed to the global economic downturn that impacted the industrialized countries. Most of the discussions on the issue has been outside the framework of the UNFCCC.The high level advisory group on finance appointed by the United nations Secretary General to look into the question of sources of long term finance, has provided a variety of sources without ranking them or indicating preferences.
