VJorhat, July 3: Tea gardens in Golaghat, Karbi Anglong and Jorhat districts may soon turn to rainwater harvesting in response to change in climate and have sought help from IIT Guwahati. The chairman of the North Eastern Tea Association (NETA), Bidyananda Barkakoty, said a primary study carried out by IIT Guwahati on the impact of climate change on the water resources of the Brahmaputra basin had revealed that there would be significant changes in rainfall pattern and temperature in the future. High intensity rainfall of shorter duration and longer dry spells will affect the flood and drought scenario, Barkakoty told this correspondent. He said rainwater harvesting had become necessary for the tea gardens to withstand the long dry spells. There are nearly 160 tea gardens in the organised sectors in the three districts. Barkakoty said a seminar on climate change and water management issues was held at the associations office in Golaghat Friday. It was attended by scientists from IIT Guwahati, Tea Board officials and tea planters from the three districts. The seminar was organised by the Tea Board in association with IIT Guwahati and was coordinated by the association. A group of experts from IIT Guwahati visited several tea gardens in Karbi Anglong and Golaghat districts in the last couple of days to collect data on the impact of climate change and water management in the tea gardens. The team included professor A.K. Sarma and professor S.K. Deb. Barkakoty said the experts from IIT have expressed their willingness to help out the planters to take a scientific approach towards rainwater harvesting using the latest technology. The executive director of Tea Board, Rakesh Saini, who attended the seminar, said water management in tea gardens had assumed greater significance in recent times, as climate change footprints were visible in the region. The geographical and time pattern of rainfall is changing erratically and temperatures are rising. These variations require revisiting the available techniques of water management in tea gardens. Indigenous, innovative and cost-effective techniques of harvesting rainwater have become unavoidable, he said. Barkakoty said the IIT team had also expressed concern about the large chunks of land being eroded by the change in the courses of rivers in the three districts. Large chunks of land in many tea estates located on the banks of rivers in the three districts have been lost because of massive erosion. He said the experts had expressed concern about natural water outlets of many tea estates being blocked because of road construction and other development activities resulting in waterlogging in these gardens. Many gardens in Golaghat, Jorhat and Karbi Anglong are facing the problem of waterlogging in the rainy season due to blocking of the natural outlets. We have been asked by the IIT experts to take up the matter with the authorities, he added.
