VNEW DELHI: The differences of opinion in the higher echelons of the government about India's international climate change stance has now come out in the open with a WikiLeaks cable showing senior leaders Jairam Ramesh , in his role as environment minister, and Montek Singh Ahluwalia , deputy chairman of Planning Commission , taking divergent views on climate change in their interactions with senior US officials.A cable recording a meeting of US special envoy on climate change Todd Stern with Ahluwalia in August 2009 records, " Deputy Planning Commissioner Montek Singh Ahluwalia told S/E Stern that the developing countries' rhetoric regarding historical responsibility was a negotiating tool and while India publicly projected that it had no intention of reducing emissions, it was putting in place measures to deploy wind and solar energy that would reduce its emissions from business as usual."It has been a long standing position of developing countries that developed countries, which have eaten up carbon space in the atmosphere, should pay up for the investments needed to solve the problem and vacate the space for developing worlds to eradicate poverty and grow.In a separate meeting in January 2010 after the contentious Copenhagen Accord, a cable records the then environment minister Jairam Ramesh telling the US ambassador that he did not agree with Prime Minister Manmohan Singh's interpretation of the letters written by UN secretary general Ban Ki Moon and Danish PM Rasmussen insisting on legally binding emission commitments from India.The cable notes, "Ramesh stated that India is ready to 'carry its domestic commitments forward' and could send its mitigation actions to the UNFCCC 'within about two hours'." He claimed that letters from the UN secretary general and the Danish PM had "muddied the waters".Ramesh said these communications could be read to imply that the submissions under the accord were legally binding and that the accord might be seen as superseding the two-track negotiating process laid out under the Kyoto Protocol and Bali Roadmap. Prime Minister Singh had replied in a January 18 letter seeking clarification. Ramesh said he did not necessarily read the letters this way but, nonetheless, they had opened questions that the PM felt must be answered before the government of India could proceed. Ramesh said he expected a clarification from the UNFCCC, and had spoken to Yvo de Boer about it.After the PM's letter, the government took stance different from one Ramesh prescribed and supported the accord but subscribed its domestic targets with several conditions that ensured the accord did not immediately become operational.Prior to the Copenhagen accord that was signed in December 2009, the US special envoy had met Ramesh and Ahluwalia. The cable records that the then environment minister "Jairam Ramesh discussed the domestic politics of a Copenhagen agreement noting that as a politician, he had to sell the agreement to his constituency. He stated that the Indian system will find it infinitely easier to accept something legislated domestically than imposed internationally. Ramesh said he would look at legislating various mitigation plans found in India's National Action Plan on Climate Change in order to give them the force of law. S/E Stern welcomed the proposal and asked whether it would be possible to use executive regulation as opposed to legislation. Ramesh affirmed that while it was possible, legislation was necessary in order to gain credibility, because there is a sanctity to a law".
