VNEW DELHI: India took a long step back into the developing world camp and towards its original international stance with Union environment minister Jayanthi Natarajan demanding much greater commitment from the developed countries before India even begins to discuss a legally binding agreement on climate change . She was speaking at a two-day informal ministerial gathering at Pretoria, South Africa, ahead of the full-blown negotiations in Durban in December.She demanded that equity be put at the heart of the climate negotiations and that rich countries first commit to addressing their historical responsibility before asking anything more of emerging economies like India, indicating that Jairam Ramesh 's 'flexibility' era was over.For India, this was a radical move away from the approach Natarajan's predecessor had taken in his tenure as environment minister.Ramesh had agreed to begin discussions on a legally binding deal. In contrast, Natarajan took a stand that got the support of other developing countries as well. "At this stage, we do not have to discuss the nature of a legally binding agreement," she said in her statement that sources said had the developed countries irked and the developing countries collectively in support.India's stand under Ramesh had shifted steadily in agreeing to an international climate deal that moved away from the existing terms of negotiations. The existing convention and international agreements squarely put the responsibility on the developed countries to be the first and substantial movers on reducing emissions. Over two years \u2013 at Copenhagen and Cancun \u2013 Ramesh had taken the lead to accept mutations that would ultimately alter the balance and bring a regime where emerging economies would take on binding commitments as well."Stabilisation of climate is based on the actions that are taken to reduce the stock of emissions. We cannot avoid this historical fact even if it may not be palatable to some of us," Natarajan said taking a shot at countries like US that have balked at the talk of carbon space and its equitable distribution.Sources told TOI that when the US special envoy on climate change, Todd Stern, used Jairam Ramesh's earlier statements to counter India's position, Natarajan deftly handled the moment stating, "Let me now turn to the remarks of my predecessor who was just quoted. When he talked of a domestically legally binding framework of actions, Minister Ramesh did so in the context of balanced and comprehensive outcomes in the two-track process. In the current scenario, I do not see the assurance of a balance." To cut the jargon, she 're-interpreted' Ramesh to say that without strong emission reduction targets by developed countries on Kyoto Protocol, progress could not be made on an over-arching deal where emerging economies take on greater responsibility of a legally binding nature.This statement came amidst the Europeans wondering aloud what was the advantage of continuing with Kyoto Protocol if some rich countries wanted out and the US demanding a new deal regardless by December 2011."As a developing country, India has already taken substantial and ambitious actions at great cost. However, in the above scenario that I just described (where rich countries are not doing enough), the issue of a legally binding agreement has acquired huge political sensitivities in India. I am guided by a political consensus in my country," Natarajan told the gathering.She added, "Equity is more fundamental and needs to be brought into our discourse to define the frame within which the global peaking (of emissions) is addressed, the equitable access to sustainable development is ensured and the nature of outcomes is determined."With threats from developed countries that talks at Durban in December could fail unless emerging economies start discussing their legally binding commitments, Natarajan countered by stating, "In our anxiety to rush towards Durban outcomes therefore, we should avoid putting the cart before the horse," implying that India was not keen upon talks on a legally binding deal even before it was known what the developed countries were bringing to table.She bolstered her argument saying, "There can be no guarantee of effective stabilization unless the developed country parties who have the largest share of historical stock of emissions agree to reach their peak. In the absence of a time frame for Annex-I peaking, any talk of global peak will remain a pious wish."At another occasion in the two-day meeting, the minister reiterated that India was doing more than its fair bit already on climate change and said, "Voluntary actions that India has announced are a part of our development strategy. But, all these actions cost a tremendous amount of resources. We are in the process of assessing the costs of implementing this strategy. It is fundamental that the global mechanisms should help in providing resources (for this strategy)."
