VKOLKATA: Rampant construction and poor compensatory plantation are taking a toll on Kolkata's environment. And it has probably never been as stark and quick as in the last year. The city's green cover now stands at a dismal 5%, which is way below the requirement of 15% for metros.In the last 12 months, Kolkata and its adjoining areas have lost more than 5,000 trees to developmental projects, unauthorized chopping and natural causes. The loss is unprecedented, says the forest department . This could have brought the cover further down and has pushed up the carbon count by an alarming 5,500,000 kg per year, the department admitted.According to the National Commission on Urbanization , which compiled the data, open spaces in the city have been vanishing as well. Less than 1% of city space now remains vacant. In north Kolkata, greenery has dipped to 4.79% which is extremely unhealthy, say experts. South Kolkata was marginally greener.The impact of this loss would be felt in the coming years, feel environmentalists. And it could be irreversible, given the sporadic and unplanned compensatory plantation in Kolkata. The figures confirm the fear. As much as 95 lakh tonnes of carbon are generated in Kolkata from vehicular emission every year. Since each full-grown tree can absorb around 1,100 kg of carbon a year, a loss of 5,000 plants means 5,500,000 kg more carbon in the city's atmosphere."The city can't hold this carbon load for long. Other than carbon, trees also absorb a whole lot of pollutants like sulphur dioxide, nitrogen, polyaromatic hydrocarbons and suspended particulate matter apart from benzene, lead and arasol. This can turn out to be a major health hazard," said Sudipto Bhattacharya of Saviours and Friends of Environment (SAFE), a green NGO.These pollutants can trigger a whole lot of diseases like asthma, skin allergies, cardiac disorders, loss of memory and diseases of the central nervous system," said Debashish Basu, preventive medicine specialist.Poor compensatory plantation, forest officials say, has contributed generously to the dwindling green count. The rulebook says that for every tree felled, at least five must be planted. Not many have paid heed. The law also says that before a tree is chopped, the forest department must be informed.The latter levies a charge for the felling and gives its sanction only after receiving an undertaking that trees will be planted to neutralize the loss. However, only a few high-profile projects have adhered to the rules.In comparison, the green cover in Delhi and Mumbai are much higher. While the Capital has a cover of 19.09%, Mumbai was marginally behind at around 18%. The national average stands at a healthier 19.49%.The erosion of greenery in the city has also led to a loss of biodiversity. Along with birds that nest in them, trees also play host to species like bats, rhesus monkeys, palm civet cats and squirrels, which have been disappearing from the city proper."An average Kolkata tree attracts around 200 species of insects that depend on it for survival. With each tree being chopped, we are also killing these or dislocating them. Compensatory plantation may help maintain the overall greenery but the loss of biodiversity is permanent," explained Pranabesh Sanyal, environmentalist and former director of Sundarban Tiger Reserve (STR).While the Cyclone Aila felled around 1000 trees, the East-West Metro project resulted in a loss of 700 trees only in Salt Lake. Around a thousand more were axed along VIP Road, BT Road and the EM Bypass. Hundreds of others fell prey to unauthorized chopping. Tarak Mohan Das, former head of the department of botany, Calcutta University , said development projects can be undertaken without chopping off trees."In many foreign cities, roads have been built keeping trees and small saplings in the middle," Das said.Even though the Kolkata Municipal Corporation (KMC) and the forest department claim to have planted 30,000 saplings each every year since 2007, the results have been dismal. Contrary to the claims that 80% of these have survived, NGOs and experts argued that the survival rate was not more than 10%-15%. Maintenance is poor and there is no trace of most of the saplings."The culture of tending to saplings is absent in Kolkata and there is hardly any monitoring. We had distributed 1,100 saplings among various organizations over the last one year as an experiment. When we followed up with them to check if the saplings were still there, we found that none had gone back to the spot," said Bhattacharya.Experts predicted that Kolkata will soon have a few green islands surrounded by large bastions of barren, concrete tracts. "The lopsided distribution of greenery is inevitable. It is better than having a treeless city, but can never compensate for the loss that the environment suffers due to the shrinking green cover," said Sanyal.
