V\u201cAs the need evolves, green jobs will become more specialised, which will then open up specialised training courses,\u201d says PepsiCo India executive director ( HR ) Pavan Bhatia. At present, institutions like Delhi University, Pune University, JNU, TERI in Delhi and Tata Institute of Social Sciences (TISS) in Mumbai; School of Planning and Architecture, and several IITs, among others, run \u2018green\u2019 courses across levels like the Bachelors\u2019, Masters\u2019 MTech/ME, and even PhDs.\u000a\u000aCarbon finance courses are offered at IIMs Ahmedabad and Lucknow. Prodipto Ghosh, member of the Prime Minister\u2019s panel on climate change, believes a wide set of skills are required in the country, and companies are looking at fresh recruits with an understanding of the problems.\u000a\u000aPeople like Richa Gautam, 25, assistant manager in the sustainability cell at Mahindra and Mahindra, was pursuing her PhD in environment management from National Institute of Industrial Engineering, Mumbai, when she landed her job. \u201cOne needs to be passionate about the environment,\u201d she says, listing the qualifications. \u201cMy job involves visiting various plants and teaching workers about how sustainability helps create energy-efficient machinery and reduces carbon emissions.\u201d\u000a\u000aFor those looking for an alternative career, the green sector offers various opportunities. Working with an NGO, or a training programme on sustainability, can help one gain the necessary perspective. Then, organisations like ACC Cement, Ecosmart, SGS India, TCS, Reliance Energy and M&M offer internships and may even recruit the interns.\u000a\u000aSays SG Choudhary, chief sustainability and technology officer at Tata Chemicals: \u201cWe are planning to bring in environmental engineers and economists on board in the coming months, to help us cut down on environmental waste and chart out a course for the future.\u201d There is even demand for the more niche areas within the green sector, like carbon or energy management, and developing clean technology.\u000a\u000aGreen jobs are, unfortunately, still not viewed as lucrative. And that\u2019s mainly because of a lack of awareness, says Sonam Madav, who did a postgraduate programme in sustainability from the University of Leeds. While entry-level salaries are about Rs3.5 to Rs4.5 lakh per annum, packages in the mid-level can vary from Rs14-20 lakh and a senior professional could even command anything between Rs45 and 60 lakh, says Balaji of MaFoi.\u000a\u000aAs such specialised talent is still at a premium, compensation packages, are going up. Also, companies like Wipro setting aside a large part of their budget to go clean, helps. \u201cWe spend a major portion of our revenue on environment-related projects,\u201d says PS Narayan, general manager and head of CSR at Wipro. \u201cWith rising need, many more people will be required in the coming years.\u201d\u000a\u000aAnd it\u2019s not just the professionals. Entrepreneurs like Nidhi Singh of Indigreen, which retails T-shirts and accessories made from organic material, says: \u201cOrganic farming is also a green job that many companies will soon take to. Such jobs not only profit corporates, but will also provide employment to large populations of rural folk too. That\u2019s why green jobs will always have the upper hand.\u201d
