VKOLKATA: Beginning later this month, the jatropha crop will be planted across 30,000 acres in the arid districts of Bankura, Birbhum, West Midnapore and Purulia over the next 15 years. Around 10 lakh saplings will be transplanted this year on 1,000 acres in Purulia, with the annual plantation target from next year pegged at 20 lakh saplings on 2,000 acres.The drive, undertaken jointly by state-promoted West Bengal Wasteland Development Corporation (WBWDC) and private firm Sun Plant Agro Ltd , is in sync with the Centre's Green India Mission to combat climate change by setting an ambitious target of afforestation and eco-restoration on 20 million hectares across India by 2020.Speaking to TOI, WBWDC managing director and additional principal chief conservator of forests Rakesh Sinha said jatropha would be grown between rows of fast-growing pulp species of trees planted on 3,000 acres in Purulia this year. "We have planted nearly 16 lakh trees already. Jatropha plantation will be done between these rows. This will not only enhance the economic output from the land that has been lying non-productive, but will also enhance the climate change mitigation efforts by promoting the use of bio-fuel," said Sinha.According to him, the jatropha plants will begin yielding 1,000 kg of seeds per acre from the third year, generating revenue of around `10,000. Of this, 30% each will go to land-owners and the forest department, while the remaining will go to Sun Agro. Planting began on Friday in the Hura, Puncha and Burrabazar areas of Purulia. The trees will be felled after they mature in 10 years and new ones will take their place. The proceeds will be split between the forest department and land-owners.The programme will also lead to the generation of carbon credits under the clean development mechanism (CDM) instituted by the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. The credits will be divided equally between the forest department and Sun Agro."Apart from the larger 