VLONDON: Business leaders of hundreds of companies from around the world, including India, have released a renewed demand for "an ambitious, robust and equitable global deal on climate change".They say companies companies are already investing in a low-carbon future and governments must respond to this by both redoubling efforts to secure an international framework but also by pursuing an ambitious "parallel mitigation strategy".The statement - known as The Cancun Communique - is an initiative of the Prince of Wales's Corporate Leaders Group on Climate Change, which is a cross-sectoral group of major international companies working with the University of Cambridge to call for more ambitious action to tackle climate change, a university release said.The Communique was presented by corporate leaders from the group to European Commissioner for Climate Action , Connie Hedegaard, and the Ambassador of Mexico to the EU, H E Sandra Fuentes-Berain in Brussels yesterday.They were joined by Ambassadors and Government Representatives from the European Parliament, Australia, Canada, Japan, India, South Africa, Turkey, UK, and US.Commissioner Hedegaard said: "Major investments are needed to develop a low-carbon economy and for Europe to continue to lead in this field.This will require a continued involvement of the private sector, along with ambitious and proactive interventions by governments".This is part of a series of events to present the Communiqu to decision makers around the world and invite further support from the business community.The Cancun Communiqu is the successor to previous communiqus such as the Bali, Poznan, and Copenhagen Communiqus.The Cancun Communiqu has already secured the support of more than 250 companies based in over 36 countries, and is expected to gather much more support before UN negotiators meet in Cancun, on 29 November.Communiqu signatories include some of the world's largest companies and best known brands in the energy, professional services, transport, technology, manufacturing, telecommunications and banking sectors from countries including the EU, Mexico, US, Japan, Australia, Canada, Brazil, India, China and South Africa.
