VINCHEON (SOUTH KOREA): India's efforts on disaster risk reduction came in for praise by the United Nations at the recently concluded 4th Asian Ministerial Conference on Disaster Risk Reduction ( DRR ) hosted by South Korea's National Emergency Management Agency here.Margareta Wahistrom, special representative of the UN secretary-general on DRR, said India did a commendable job in the post-tsunami rehabilitation work and has since taken a number of steps towards reduction of disaster risk. She, however, called for the government to incorporate DRR in its national policy to cope with climate change.The four-day ministerial conference called for governments to earmark at least 10% of all rescue and rehabilitation funds towards disaster risk reduction. It also adopted a five-year regional roadmap on DRR and climate change adaptation, which includes capacity building activities, enhanced information sharing and solutions to manage climate risks using various technologies.India has been effectively using technology such as SMS, radio, television, watch towers and loudspeakers in disaster risk zones to communicate to its population on eviction in time of danger. It is in the process of activating a regional warning centre on gathering seismological and tidal data to send out alerts to coastal regions. Currently, the warning centre on seismological data is in Japan and Hawaii which have been sending alerts to national agencies in Indian Ocean countries.Highlighting the importance for countries like India to invest in disaster risk, the UN official said since half of the world GDP falls in the disaster risk zone, countries which have not invested in DRR are more likely to fail in achieving their full economic potential.A new joint report from the World Bank and the United Nations, released last week, said annual global losses from natural disasters could triple to $185 billion by the end of this century, even without calculating the impact of climate change.Climate change could then add $28 to $68 billion more in damages each year from tropical cyclones alone, the report said. The report also said that the number of people exposed to storms and earthquakes in large cities could double to 1.5 billion by 2050.The 250-page report, `Natural Hazards, Unnatural Disasters: The Economics of Effective Prevention' was targeted at the world's finance ministers and stressed on prevention as that alone pays to mitigate the economic impact.It went on to suggest removing rent controls, something India can take notice of as the report pointed out that by doing so, it would bring in incentives for landlords to maintain buildings and thus result in less number of mishaps and deaths. This is important, in view of how a poorly constructed building in Delhi collapsed resulting in 67 deaths.
