VChief Minister Narendra Modi has penned down his first book in English  on climate change. Previously he has penned short stories,poetry and even essays,but they were written originally in Gujarati.\u000a\u000aTitled Convenient Action: Gujarats Response to Challenges of Climate Change, the book primarily focuses on how Gujarat has responded to the challenges of climate change  the biggest challenge to the world at present.\u000a\u000aThe state government claims to be the only provincial government in the Sub-Continent to have a dedicated climate change department.\u000a\u000aTo be released on December 21 in the presence of Kalam,it will be CMs first book in English\u000a\u000aThe book launch invite calls it a green autobiography by one of the reviewers  Steve Howard. The fact that the Gujarat government has gone ahead and set up its own full-fledged department of climate change is a clear declaration of intent and shows that the actions have been well-planned and thought through, reads Howards comments.\u000a\u000aThe book runs into 250 pages with lots of photos,charts and texts in four colours. It is published by Macmillan Publishers India Limited and is available in both hardback and paperback.\u000a\u000aThe book is yet to be available in the market,but senior executives at Macmillan say the book discusses in great detail the water resources and pollution and how the state government has taken pro-active action to meet the challenges of climate change.\u000a\u000aThe book contains all recent unpublished data on climate change in original form. Modi is the most progressive CM as he chose to write on an issue concerning the society at large rather than his own life,the official said. Modis book release,he added,will be the companys biggest ever launch in India.\u000a\u000aAsked why the chief minister chose Macmillan over any other publishing house,the official said Macmillan is Indias oldest publication house and has operations all over the world,which will give international visibility to the book. That is why Modi probably chose Macmillan, he said.\u000a\u000aIncidentally,Modi is the second politician after former US Vice-President Al Gore to write a book on climate change.\u000a\u000aThe book will be released on December 21 at a function to be presided over by former President APJ Abdul Kalam. Climate change expert R K Pachauri,chairman of the Nobel Laureate committee,Inter-governmental Panel on Climate Change,will attend the function as a guest of honour.\u000a\u000aFor all the latest Ahmedabad News, download Indian Express App
